INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (1,'<p>Which of the following is an example of a mand?</p>','2017-05-14 08:30:28','<p><strong>Mand</strong>&nbsp;is a term that&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B.F._Skinner" title="B.F. Skinner">B.F. Skinner</a>&nbsp;used to describe a verbal&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operant_conditioning" title="Operant conditioning">operant</a>&nbsp;in which the response is reinforced by a characteristic consequence and is therefore under the functional control of relevant conditions of deprivation or aversive stimulation. One cannot determine, based on form alone, whether a response is a mand; it is necessary to know the kinds of variables controlling a response in order to identify a verbal operant. A mand is sometimes said to &quot;specify its reinforcement&quot; although this is not always the case. Skinner introduced the mand as one of six primary verbal operants in his 1957 work,&nbsp;<em><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Verbal_Behavior" title="Verbal Behavior">Verbal Behavior</a></em>.</p>',1,1,14,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (2,'<p>Who is the founder of Radical Behaviorism?</p>','2017-05-14 11:36:50','<p><strong>B.F. Skinner </strong>was the pioneer who founded <em>radical behaviorism,</em> which can be distinguished from the <em>methodological behaviorism</em> that preceded it by it&#39;s inclusion of thinking, feeling, and other private events in the analysis of animal behaviors.</p>

<p>Some of the concepts to emerge from Skinner&#39;s work include:</p>

<ul>
	<li>The cumulative record</li>
	<li>The S-R-S contingency or <em>Operant Conditioning</em></li>
	<li>The &quot;Skinner Box&quot; (or <em>Operant Chamber)</em></li>
</ul>',1,1,39,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (3,'<p>Which antecedent increases or decreases the value of a consequence?</p>','2017-05-14 11:37:47','<p>There are at least two general&nbsp;<strong>types</strong>&nbsp;of antecedents, three if you count prompts:</p>

<p style="margin-left:40px"><strong>- SD:</strong> short for <em>discriminative stimulus</em> - the SD correlates with the availability of a reinforcer</p>

<p style="margin-left:40px"><strong>- MO:</strong> short for&nbsp;<em>motivating operation</em>, the MO alters the momentary probability of a behavior and value of a consequence from moment to moment.</p>

<p>Motivating operations can be further sub-divided based on their value-altering effect:&nbsp;<em>Establishing Operations</em> <u>increase</u> the value of a consequence (as a reinforcer/punisher) and&nbsp;<em>Abolishing Operations</em><em> <u>decrease</u></em> the value of a consequence (as a reinforcer or punisher).</p>',1,1,25,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (4,'<p>Billy sees a <u>sign for a gas station</u> and gasoline has typically been available in the past when Billy sees a sign for a gas station.</p>

<p>What type of antecedent is the <u><em>sight of the gas station sign</em></u>?</p>','2017-05-19 07:42:54','<p>There are at least two general&nbsp;<strong>types</strong>&nbsp;of antecedents, three if you count prompts:</p>

<p>- SD: short for <em>discriminative stimulus</em>, and SD signals the availability of a reinforcer</p>

<p>- MO: short for&nbsp;<em>motivating operation</em>, the MO alters the value of a consequence from moment to moment.</p>

<p>There are&nbsp;two types of motivating operations:&nbsp;<em>Establishing Operations</em>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<em>Abolishing Operations</em>.&nbsp;</p>

<p>EO, or&nbsp;<strong>Establishing Operations</strong>, increase the value of a consequence, whereas&nbsp;an AO (<strong>Abolishing Operation</strong>) decreases the vlaue of a consequence over time.</p>',1,1,25,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (5,'<p>Classical conditioning is also commonly referred to as...</p>','2017-05-21 15:00:21','<h2 style="font-style:italic"><strong>Pavlov&#39;s Experiment: Pairing &amp; Respondent Relations</strong></h2>

<p><img alt="Pavlov''s Experiment" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/ec/MonumentIPAVLOV.jpg" style="border-style:solid; border-width:3px; float:left; height:231px; margin:5px; width:150px" />Pavlov&#39;s experiment famously (and serrendipitously) documented&nbsp;a process by which a stimulus (S1) can be paired with second stimulus (S2) to cause that second stimulus to impact behavior in the same way as that first stimulus.</p>

<p><u>For Example...</u></p>

<ul style="margin-left:160px">
	<li>The&nbsp;<strong>first stimulus</strong> elicits some reflex (i.e., salivating, an increased heart beat, a startle response) and is associated with a biological need - hunger, sleep, sexual behavior, or even a biological &quot;need for activity.&quot;</li>
	<li>The&nbsp;<strong>second stimulus</strong>&nbsp;is neutral - that is to say, it has no current impact on behavior</li>
	<li>The first stimulus and second stimulus are repeatedly presented together at the same time (<strong>paired</strong>)</li>
	<li>After some period of time, the organism will begin to react to the second stimulus as if it were the first - this is called <em>conditioning!</em></li>
</ul>

<p>This is process is now commonly known as <strong>Classical Conditioning</strong>, <strong>Pavlovian conditioning</strong>, or&nbsp;<strong>Respondent Conditioning</strong>. While the names are very different, they do commonly refer to this pairing process.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h2 style="font-style:italic"><strong>Types of Conditioning</strong></h2>

<p>There are many types of conditioning, which can have an impact on how the organism learns. The effect on learning can be to make it more efficient or less efficient. This is done by manipulating the temporal arrangement (<em>order in time</em>)&nbsp;of the&nbsp;<em>Conditioned Stimulus</em>&nbsp;(abbreviated as CS) and the&nbsp;<em>Unconditioned Stimulus</em>&nbsp;(abbreviated as US).&nbsp;Here are some examples (keep in mind this is not an exhaustive list):</p>

<ul>
	<li><strong>Forward Conditioning:</strong>&nbsp;learning is fastest in forward conditioning. During forward conditioning, the onset of the CS precedes the onset of the US.</li>
</ul>

<ul>
	<li><strong>Simultaneous Conditioning:</strong>&nbsp;during simultaneous conditioning, the CS and US are presented and terminated at the same time</li>
</ul>

<ul>
	<li><strong>Backwards Conditioning:</strong>&nbsp;backward conditioning occurs when a CS immediately follows a US, and usually has the opposite effect as forward conditioning: that is to say, the organism learns that the CS signals the end of the US.&nbsp;</li>
</ul>

<ul>
	<li><strong>Extinction:&nbsp;</strong>the CS is repeatedly presented but the US does not follow. This, of course, must be done after the CS is already conditioned</li>
</ul>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>',1,1,13,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (6,'<p>Which of the following is a type of&nbsp;<strong><u>CONTINUOUS</u></strong>&nbsp;data collection method?</p>','2017-05-31 04:23:50','<h2 style="font-style:italic">Continuous Measurement&nbsp;</h2>

<p>Continuous measurement data collection systems&nbsp;<u>capture every possible occurence</u>&nbsp;of a behavior of interest. Some of the benefits of continuous measurement systems is they capture every instance of the behavior, therefore, are much more accurate than discontinuous data collection systems. However, as you can imagine, it can be very burdensome to implement a continuous data collection system (such as a frequency count) for a behavior that is very high-rate or near constant. Similarly, if you are a teacher working in a classroom of twenty or thirty kids, constantly measuring the behavior of just one student while tending to the needs of all the others would be a real challenge!</p>

<p>So while continuous measurement systems are excellent at providing a complete record of the behavior of interest, they are limited by the resources available - it might just not be possible or practical to require data collectors to count each incident of behavior in some way.</p>

<h3><strong>Continuous measurement systems come in a variety of different common types, as follows:</strong></h3>

<ul>
	<li><strong>Frequency</strong>&nbsp;- counting each individual event</li>
	<li><strong>Inter-Response Time</strong>&nbsp;- counting the time from the&nbsp;<u>offset</u>&nbsp;(end) of one response, to the&nbsp;<u>onset</u>&nbsp;(start) of the next response.</li>
	<li><strong>Duration</strong>&nbsp;-&nbsp;the number of seconds from the&nbsp;<u>onset</u>&nbsp;(start) of the&nbsp;response&nbsp;to the&nbsp;<u>offset</u>&nbsp;(end) of the response.</li>
</ul>

<hr />
<h2 style="font-style:italic">&nbsp;</h2>

<h2 style="font-style:italic">Discontinuous Measurement&nbsp;</h2>

<p>Discontinuous measurement systems only capture a percentage of the behavior of interest. While they are, as a result of this, inherently less accurate than continuous measurement systems, they are much easier to implement as recording each instance of the behavior is not necessary. Instead, data collectors only need to record a &quot;yes&quot; or &quot;no&quot; value for blocks of time during an interval based off specific criteria, as follows:</p>

<ul>
	<li><strong>Whole-Interval Data Recording</strong>&nbsp;- recording the behavior&nbsp;<u>ONLY</u>&nbsp;if the behavior occurs for the entire interval (from the beginning until the end of the interval, without stopping!)</li>
	<li><strong>Partial-Interval Data Recording</strong>&nbsp;- recording the behavior if it happens at any point in the entire interval.</li>
	<li><strong>Momentary Time Sampling</strong>- recording the behavior if it happens ONLY at a specific moment at time, between the intervals. For example, if you were observing every 5 minutes, you&#39;d set a timer for 5 minutes and look up upon the timer&#39;s alarm and identify (yes or no) if the behavior is occurring in that instant and that instant only.</li>
</ul>

<p>There are different pro&#39;s and con&#39;s of each time of discontinuos data recording type. Whole-interval recording is great for behaviors you want to see increase for the entirety of an interval, such as, say, staying in your seat during math class. Partial-interval recording is useful when you want to see a behavior decrease or not exist at all during an interval, such as tantrums during homework time. Finally, Momentary Time Sampling is useful for recording the behavior of large groups of individuals (for whom it would be just too cumbersome to individually record), such as kids playing on a playground appropriately vs inappropriately (whatever your definition of &quot;appropriate&quot; is).</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>A Discontinuos Sampling Measurement Example:</strong></p>

<p>Consider the following example to illistrate how different types of discontinuous measurement systems may report completely different (and possibly misleading!) results from the exact same data set:</p>

<p>Perhaps you are recording data on the following behavior-of-interest, &quot;screaming during circle time.&quot; The student engages in screaming at the following points in time:</p>

<ul>
	<li>from 9:03 - 9:06, for about 3 minutes and 33 seconds</li>
	<li>from, 9:10 - 9:15, for 5 minutes and 15 seconds</li>
	<li>from 9:21 - 9:22, for about 30 seconds</li>
</ul>

<p>The total duration of screaming (in terms of&nbsp;<strong>duration</strong>, which is, remember, a&nbsp;<u>continuous</u>&nbsp;measurement) is <strong>9 minutes, 18 seconds&nbsp;</strong>out of a period of 25 minutes (about 36% occurence of the total duration for circle time)</p>

<p>We would record a &quot;0&quot; below if the behavior met criteria, and an &quot;X&quot; if it meets criteria. As discontinous measurement records, they would appear as follows:</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h3><u><strong>Screaming During Circle Time:&nbsp;</strong>Whole-Interval Data Recording</u>:</h3>

<table border="1" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; border:1px solid black; width:500px">
	<tbody>
		<tr>
			<td style="text-align:center; width:20%">9:00 - 9:05</td>
			<td style="text-align:center; width:20%">9:05 - 9:10</td>
			<td style="text-align:center; width:20%">9:10 - 9:15</td>
			<td style="text-align:center; width:20%">9:15 - 9:20</td>
			<td style="text-align:center; width:20%">9:20 - 9:25</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style="background-color:#eeeeee; text-align:center">0</td>
			<td style="background-color:#eeeeee; text-align:center">0</td>
			<td style="background-color:#66ccff; text-align:center"><strong>X</strong></td>
			<td style="background-color:#eeeeee; text-align:center">0</td>
			<td style="background-color:#eeeeee; text-align:center">0</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody>
</table>

<p>Thus, for our data set, a whole-interval data recording would report <strong>a 20% occurrence rate (1 / 5).</strong></p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h3><u><strong>Screaming During Circle Time:&nbsp;</strong>Partial-Interval Data Recording</u>:</h3>

<table border="1" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; border:1px solid black; width:500px">
	<tbody>
		<tr>
			<td style="text-align:center; width:20%">9:00 - 9:05</td>
			<td style="text-align:center; width:20%">9:05 - 9:10</td>
			<td style="text-align:center; width:20%">9:10 - 9:15</td>
			<td style="text-align:center; width:20%">9:15 - 9:20</td>
			<td style="text-align:center; width:20%">9:20 - 9:25</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style="background-color:#66ccff; text-align:center">X</td>
			<td style="background-color:#66ccff; text-align:center">X</td>
			<td style="background-color:#66ccff; text-align:center">X</td>
			<td style="background-color:#eeeeee; text-align:center">0</td>
			<td style="background-color:#66ccff; text-align:center">X</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody>
</table>

<p>Thus, for our data set, a whole-interval data recording would report <strong>a 80% occurrence rate (4 / 5).</strong></p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h3><u><strong>Screaming During Circle Time:&nbsp;</strong>Momentary-Time Sample Recording</u>:</h3>

<table border="1" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; border:1px solid black; width:500px">
	<tbody>
		<tr>
			<td style="text-align:center; width:20%">9:00 - 9:05</td>
			<td style="text-align:center; width:20%">9:05 - 9:10</td>
			<td style="text-align:center; width:20%">9:10 - 9:15</td>
			<td style="text-align:center; width:20%">9:15 - 9:20</td>
			<td style="text-align:center; width:20%">9:20 - 9:25</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style="background-color:#66ccff; text-align:center">X</td>
			<td style="background-color:#eeeeee; text-align:center">0</td>
			<td style="background-color:#66ccff; text-align:center">X</td>
			<td style="background-color:#66ccff; text-align:center">X</td>
			<td style="background-color:#eeeeee; text-align:center">0</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody>
</table>

<p>Thus, for our data set, a whole-interval data recording would report <strong>a 60% occurrence rate (3&nbsp;/ 5).</strong></p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><u><strong>Our Results</strong></u>:</p>

<p>Remember that the actual duration for this hypothetical behavior was 9 minutes and 18 seconds, or about 36% occurrence of the total duration of our imaginary circle time.&nbsp;</p>

<ul>
	<li><strong>Whole-Interval Data Recording</strong>&nbsp;<u>underestimated</u>&nbsp;occurrence at 20% (1 / 5 intervals as &quot;X&quot; or &quot;yes&quot;)</li>
	<li><strong>Partial-Interval Data Recording</strong>&nbsp;<u>overestimated</u>&nbsp;occurrence at 80% (4 / 5 intervals as &quot;X&quot; or &quot;yes&quot;)</li>
	<li><strong>Momentary Time Sampling</strong> Data Recording&nbsp;<u>over-estimated</u>&nbsp;occurrence at 60% (3&nbsp;intervals as &quot;X&quot; or &quot;yes&quot;)</li>
</ul>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Overall, practitioners are using discontinuous methods more and more, as they are much easier to use and can, with caution and mindfulness, be effective at representing an intervention&#39;s impact on a behavior in a useful way. However, as you can see from the example above, incorrect use of discontinous sampling methods could mislead practitioners and misrepresent reality!</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><u>References</u>:</p>

<p>Fiske, K., &amp; Delmolino, L. (2012). <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3592492/">Use of Discontinuous Methods of Data Collection in Behavioral Intervention: Guidelines for Practitioners</a>.&nbsp;<em>Behavior Analysis in Practice</em>,&nbsp;<em>5</em>(2), 77&ndash;81.</p>',1,1,3,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (7,'<p>Which of the following <strong>verbal operants</strong>&nbsp;is a label or name for a non-verbal discriminative stimulus and is maintained by generalized reinforcement?</p>','2017-05-31 14:01:37','<p><strong>Tacts</strong>&nbsp;(labeling) is a verbal operant&nbsp;which is controlled by a nonverbal stimulus (such as an object, event, or property of an object) and is maintained by nonspecific (aka, &quot;generalized&quot;) social reinforcement.</p>',1,1,17,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (8,'<p>What&nbsp;<strong>verbal operant</strong>&nbsp;refers to asking for or requesting things, is under the control of an MO, and is maintained by specific reinforcement (i.e., the things the person is requesting)?</p>','2017-05-31 14:26:41','<p><strong>Mand</strong>&nbsp;is a term that&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B.F._Skinner" title="B.F. Skinner">B.F. Skinner</a>&nbsp;used to describe a verbal&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operant_conditioning" title="Operant conditioning">operant</a>&nbsp;in which the response is reinforced by a characteristic consequence and is therefore under the functional control of relevant conditions of deprivation or aversive stimulation. One cannot determine, based on form alone, whether a response is a mand; it is necessary to know the kinds of variables controlling a response in order to identify a verbal operant. A mand is sometimes said to &quot;specify its reinforcement&quot; although this is not always the case. Skinner introduced the mand as one of six primary verbal operants in his 1957 work,&nbsp;<em><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Verbal_Behavior" title="Verbal Behavior">Verbal Behavior</a></em>.</p>',1,1,14,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (9,'<blockquote>
<p>Tim, a BCBA, always writes his procedures in clear and concise terms so that his staff (and families, too!) can easily understand what is meant by his procedures. He provides complete and full definitions, and avoids using overly specific jargon when the person(s) who will be reading or implementing his procedures are laypersons.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Of the 7 Dimensions of ABA (as originally described by&nbsp;Baer, D., Wolf, M., &amp; Risley, R., 1968), which of the following does the above most closely describe?</p>','2017-05-31 16:41:59','<p>In 1968, Baer, Wolf, &amp; Risley formalized definitions for what &quot;Applied Behavior Analysis&quot; is as a science. This was the first article in the very first journal dedicated to the study of Applied Behavior Analysis, formally.Their original article can be found <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1310980/pdf/jaba00083-0089.pdf">online, for free, on the government&#39;s NCBI website for the journal of applied behavior analysis</a>&nbsp;(If you&#39;re asking yourself &quot;should I bother to read that?&quot;, the answer is yes, you should!). Their seven &quot;dimensions&quot; (aka, &quot;defining characteristics&quot;) of ABA are as follows:</p>

<ul>
	<li><strong>Applied:&nbsp;</strong>Applied interventions deal with problems of demonstrated social importance.</li>
	<li><strong>Behavioral:&nbsp;</strong>Applied interventions deal with measurable behavior (or reports if they can be validated).</li>
	<li><strong>Analytic:&nbsp;</strong>Applied interventions require an objective demonstration that the procedures caused the effect.</li>
	<li><strong>Technological:&nbsp;</strong>Applied interventions are described well enough that they can be implemented by anyone with training and resources.</li>
	<li><strong>Conceptual Systems:</strong>&nbsp;Applied interventions arise from a specific and identifiable theoretical base rather than being a set of packages or tricks.</li>
	<li><strong>Effective:&nbsp;</strong>Applied interventions produce strong, socially important effects.</li>
	<li><strong>Generality:</strong>&nbsp;Applied interventions are designed from the outset to operate in new environments and continue after the formal treatments have ended.</li>
</ul>',1,1,7,1);
