</ul>

<p><strong>Positive</strong> and <strong>Negative</strong> are terms used to refer to how the environment changes. Positive refers to <u>adding</u>&nbsp;a stimulus to the environment, whereas&nbsp;<u>negative</u>&nbsp;refers to removing a stimulus from the environment. There can be both positive and negative punishment and positive and negative reinforcement.</p>

<p>It can be useful to think of &quot;positive and negative&quot; as the first names for a consequential operation, and &quot;reinforcement and punishment&quot; as the last names. When analyzing a scenario, first, think of whether a stimulus is being added or removed - this gives you the &quot;first name&quot; (either positive or negative). Next, identify if a behavior is increasing or decreasing - this will determine the &quot;last name&quot; (punishment or reinforcement).</p>',1,1,13,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (16,'<p>Sometimes, behavior analysts will break down&nbsp;a complex chain of behaviors&nbsp;into smaller discrete steps to facilitate teaching.</p>

<p>The learner will then be taught to complete the steps in their logical order, with the completion of the previous step serving as the reinforcer for that step and the discriminative stimulus (SD) for the next step. Finally, the last step in the chain (terminal step) serves as the reinforcer for the whole chain.</p>

<p>What is this called?</p>','2017-05-31 20:23:56','<p>A <strong>task analysis</strong> is used by behavior analysts to break a complicated task down into a more easily accomplishable sequence of smaller, simpler steps.</p>

<p><strong>Chaining</strong>&nbsp;is the process by which one behavior is linked to another, such that the reinforcer for the all steps in the chain (except the last step) is the completion of that step, which also serves as the SD for the next step. The final step&#39;s completion usually contacts a conditioned / unconditioned reinforcer that serves as a reinforcer for the whole chain!</p>

<p>An example of a task analysis could be making a sandwich:</p>

<ol>
	<li>Open a bag of bread</li>
	<li>Take two slices out</li>
	<li>Lay them on a plate, side-by-side</li>
	<li>Get the jar of peanut butter</li>
	<li>Get a knife</li>
	<li>Spread the peanut butter on one side of the bread</li>
	<li>Wipe the knife off in the sink, and keep it with you</li>
	<li>Put the jar of peanut butter back</li>
	<li>Get a jar of jelly</li>
	<li>Spread some jelly on the other side of the bread</li>
	<li>Wipe the knife off in the sink and put it on the dry rack</li>
	<li>Put the two sandwich slices together</li>
	<li>Enjoy!</li>
</ol>

<p>In the task analysis above, you might notice that some of the steps (such as steps 4 - 10) can be completed in a different order and still achieve the same effect. For instance, you could absolutely put the jelly on before the peanut butter. However, it would make little sense to do step 12 befor edoing steps 2 - 10. Sometimes, the&nbsp;<strong>logical order</strong>&nbsp;of the steps may be&nbsp;<u>insensitive</u>&nbsp;to change (that is, you can mix them up), or it may be&nbsp;<u>sensitive</u>&nbsp;to change (that is to say if you mix them up, the terminal reinforcer will change in quality or be unavailable).</p>',1,1,16,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (18,'<blockquote>
<p>Bill is working as a paraprofessional in a classroom of twenty five children. He is very busy!&nbsp;A&nbsp;BCBA working for the school recently asked him if he could take data on a student&#39;s fingernail &quot;hoarding.&quot; More specifically, a student in his class will chew his fingernails and then store them in his pencil case or in the compartment of his desk.&nbsp;</p>

<p>Since Bill is so busy, he offerred to take data on the real or object outcomes of the behavior - in this case, at the end of the day, Bill will clean the student&#39;s desk and count any fingernail clippings he finds there (and make a note if he observes any hoarding occurring away from the desk).</p>
</blockquote>

<p><strong>In this scenario, what type of data collection is Bill using?</strong></p>','2017-06-08 20:49:30','<p><strong>Permanent Product Measurement</strong>&nbsp;refers to collecting data on the real, concrete outcomes of a behavior. Permanent products can come in many forms - such as completed homework assignments, smoked cigarettes discarded in an ash tray, or clumps of hair found on the floor.</p>

<p>For a behavior to be measured using permanent product recordings, the behavior must leave something behind following it&#39;s occurrence. This is referred to as a&nbsp;<u>product</u>. This product must last long enough to be recorded by the observer, and be reasonably representative of each occurrence of the behavior. It is up to the analyst to decide, based off the outcome, whether the correlation between product and occurrence of behavior is high enough. For instance, in a scenario involving a cigarette smoker, it is conceivable that the smoker may learn to hide or conceal cigarette butts from observers. Deceptive behavior hinders the reliability of permanent products as a data collection tool.&nbsp;</p>

<p>Permanent products are advantageous for a few reasons. Chiefly, they do not require an observe to constantly monitor the person engaging in the behavior of interest. Secondly, verification and scoring of the product can be done at a later date by an observer who may require training to score a permanent product effectively (for instance, collecting <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zaner-Bloser">Zaner-Bloser</a> data on handwriting legibility).</p>

<p>Some disadvantages of permanent product recording is that it is possible for an individual to conceal their product, altering their score. It is also conceivable that other individuals might produce a similar product, confounding their result with the behavior of the person of interest.</p>',1,1,5,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (19,'<p>Reinforcers that acquire their reinforcing properties through pairing with another reinforcer are known as...</p>','2017-06-09 20:44:40','<p><strong>Conditioned reinforcers&nbsp;</strong>gain their reinforcing properties through pairing with other conditioned or unconditioned reinforcers.</p>

<p><strong>Unconditioned reinforcers</strong>&nbsp;are things that satisfy a biological need, such as food, sleep, water, and other things that satisfy a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homeostatic">biological homeostatic need</a>. These are not learned - rather, our bodies are &quot;hard-wired&quot; to react to these stimuli as reinforcers due to their importance to the function of our bodies.</p>',1,1,13,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (20,'<p>Which of the following is true about&nbsp;<strong>cumulative records</strong>?</p>','2017-06-12 11:49:37','<p><strong>Cumulative Records</strong>&nbsp;display a &quot;running total&quot; of behaviors that have occurred over a certain time period. A special thing to note about cumulative records is that they never decrease (slope downward) because they each point on the graph is always one more (+1) than the previous.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><em>Bonus fact:</em> B.F. Skinner invented cumulative records!</p>',1,1,3,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (21,'<blockquote>
<p>Kaley, a BCaBA, is working with a young child who is learning to make his own lunch. She is collecting data on how long it takes from when she says &quot;Go make your lunch&quot; for him to initiate opening up his lunchbox and cooking his microwaveable meal. Over the course of several meals, she collects the following data:</p>

<p>Trial #1: 28s</p>

<p>Trial #2: 37s</p>

<p>Trial #3: 48s</p>

<p>Trial #4: 17s</p>

<p>Trial #5: 30s</p>
</blockquote>

<p>What type of&nbsp;<strong>data collection</strong>&nbsp;is Kaley using by measuring the time between an antecedent stimulus and the onset of a target response?</p>','2017-06-12 20:01:51','<p>Continuous measurement procedures include&nbsp;<strong>frequency</strong>&nbsp;(total event count),&nbsp;<strong>duration</strong>&nbsp;(total time),&nbsp;<strong>rate</strong>&nbsp;(frequency per unit time),&nbsp;<strong>IRT</strong>&nbsp;(time between responses), and&nbsp;<strong>latency</strong>&nbsp;(time between an antecedent stimuli and the occurence of a specific response).</p>

<p><br />
Continuous measurement procedures record (or attempt to record...) each response in some fashion. This contrasts to&nbsp;<strong>discontinuous measurement</strong>&nbsp;procedures, which record the occurrence vs non-occurrence of a behavior at a certain moment in time or across an interval of time. Some examples of discontinue measurement procedures include momentary time sampling, partial interval recording, and whole interval recording.</p>',1,1,3,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (22,'<p><strong>Response definitions</strong>, sometimes also referred to as <em><strong>operational definitions</strong></em> or <em><strong>behavior definitions</strong></em>, refer to a ...</p>','2017-06-12 20:08:16','<p>An&nbsp;<strong>operational definition</strong>&nbsp;(aka,&nbsp;<strong>response definition</strong>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<strong>behavior definition</strong>) should meet the following criteria:</p>

<ol>
	<li><strong>Objective</strong>&nbsp;- the definition, when used by multiple persons, should produce high levels of&nbsp;<u>agreement</u>&nbsp;- that is to say, the score produced by multiple people observing the same behavior would be very similar (if not exactly the same). This is referred to as <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inter-rater_reliability">inter-rater reliability or inter-observer agreement</a>.</li>
	<li><strong>Clear</strong> - there should be no ambiguity between examples / non-examples of the target behavior</li>
	<li><strong>Complete</strong>&nbsp;- there should be sufficient detail to encapsulate the target behavior in it&#39;s entirety</li>
	<li><strong>Concise</strong>&nbsp;- the description should be as short as possible without sacrificing any of the above requirements.</li>
</ol>',1,1,7,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (23,'<p>Which of the following describes&nbsp;<strong>differential reinforcement</strong>?</p>','2017-06-23 13:33:27','<p><strong>Differential Reinforcement</strong>&nbsp;is the provision of&nbsp;<strong>reinforcement</strong>&nbsp;only the appropriate response (or behavior you wish to increase) and applying extinction to all other responses.</p>

<p>Along the way, a <strong>shaping procedure</strong>&nbsp;may be used to provide reinforcement for successive approximations of the correct response - that is to say, baby steps towards independent or &quot;more correct&quot; responding (whatever that may mean in the specific case you&#39;re dealing with).</p>

<p>Usually, when a learner begins to reliably master a &quot;new step&quot;, the next step towards the best form of the response will be selected&nbsp;and only that new best form will obtain the maximal reinforcer and all other responses will be put on extinction (or, sometimes, minimal reinforcement). Extinction is the discontinuing of <strong>reinforcement</strong>&nbsp;of a previously reinforced behavior.</p>',1,1,26,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (24,'<blockquote>
<p>Todd is walking down main street. To his right, he sees a sign that says &quot;Hot &amp; Fresh Donuts.&quot; In the past, that sign has typically correlated with an increased availability of donuts (hot and fresh ones, at that!)</p>
</blockquote>

<p>What type of antecedent is the <strong>hot &amp; fresh donuts sign</strong>?</p>','2017-07-05 10:44:13','<p>There are at least two general&nbsp;<strong>types</strong>&nbsp;of antecedents, three if you count prompts:</p>

<p style="margin-left:40px"><strong>- SD:</strong> short for <em>discriminative stimulus</em> - the presence of the SD correlates with the availability of a reinforcer.</p>

<p style="margin-left:40px"><strong>- MO:</strong> short for&nbsp;<em>motivating operation</em>, the MO alters the value of a consequence from moment to moment.</p>

<p>There are&nbsp;two types of motivating operations:&nbsp;<em>Establishing Operations</em>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<em>Abolishing Operations</em>.&nbsp;</p>

<ul>
	<li>EO, or&nbsp;<strong>Establishing Operations</strong>, increase the value of a consequence, whereas&nbsp;an AO (<strong>Abolishing Operation</strong>) decreases the value of a consequence over time.</li>
</ul>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Motivating Operations</strong>&nbsp;have both&nbsp;<u>value-altering</u>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<u>behavior-altering</u>&nbsp;effects:</p>

<ol>
	<li><strong>Value-Altering:</strong>&nbsp;impacts the value of a&nbsp;<u>consequence</u>, either increasing / decreasing it&#39;s effectiveness as a reinforcer or punisher.</li>
	<li><strong>Behavior-Altering:</strong>&nbsp;increases or decreases the momentary frequency (&quot;likelihood of a behavior occurring&quot;)</li>
</ol>',1,1,25,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (25,'<p>Bill has not eaten all day, and it&#39;s almost dinner time. He sees a donut on the high shelf in the kitchen, and reaches for it while he says &quot;Donut please...&quot; in a zombie-like donut trance. Unable to reach it, he looks up at you emploringly before looking back at the donut, salivating.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>What type of <strong>verbal operant</strong> is this, generally speaking?</p>','2017-07-05 13:41:26','<p><strong>Mands&nbsp;</strong>are a verbal operant under the control of a&nbsp;<u>motivating operation</u>. In this particular example, the boy sees a donut and reaches for it - suggesting he has a MO for donuts. In addition, he begins to salivate, a reflexive response to the presence of food. This is all pretty compelling evidence that Billy is hungry, and he&#39;s <strong>manding for donuts.</strong></p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>A <strong>tact</strong> would be a label for a non-verbal stimulus that is maintained by <u>generalized reinforcement</u> - in this context, since the vocalization &quot;donuts&quot; is likely maintained by getting access to donuts (specific reinforcement) it is unlikely to be a tact.</p>',1,1,25,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (26,'<p>A boy looks up at the sky and sees a bird. He says, &quot;<strong>A bird!</strong>&quot;</p>

<p><br />
What type of verbal operant the boy&#39;s vocalization (&quot;a bird&quot;) most likely an example of?</p>','2017-07-05 15:28:55','<p>A&nbsp;<strong>tact&nbsp;</strong>is one of Skinner&#39;s elementary verbal operants. Tacts are under the antecedent control of non-verbal stimuli (like pictures, things, etc. - but&nbsp;<u>not</u>&nbsp;written words or text). Tacts are reinforced by generalized reinforcement.</p>',1,1,25,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (27,'<p>Tommy walks up to Sally and says &quot;Hey, do you know the time?&quot; and Sally responds, &quot;It is 3 o&#39;clock!&quot;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Sally&#39;s verbal behavior, in this instance, would be best classified as a what type of operant?</strong></p>','2017-07-05 15:44:47','<p>Tommy&#39;s behavior is an example of a&nbsp;<u>mand</u>: he is requesting information, or more specifically, what time it is.</p>

<p>Sally&#39;s behavior is an example of an&nbsp;<strong><u>intraverbal</u>:</strong> she is responding to Tommy&#39;s mand by providing the answer.&nbsp;</p>',1,1,25,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (28,'<p>Cathy says &quot;stop copying me!&quot; and her little brother, Billy, repeats &quot;Stop copying me!&quot;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Generally speaking, this is most closely an example of which type of verbal operant?</p>','2017-07-05 16:42:40','<p>Echoics are, essentially, repeating the vocal speech of another person.</p>',1,1,25,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (29,'<p>Sam is working with a client who engages in problem behavior during math class. Sam&#39;s client, Bob, is now working on math problem accuracy which Sam presumes may help decrease this problematic behavior. Due to time&nbsp;limitations, during therapy sessions, Sam does not have time to grade the math problems immediately - he does this work off-site using Bob&#39;s completed math worksheets as physical records of their behavior.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>In behavior analysis, the term for physical records left behind following a behavior is...</strong></p>','2017-07-06 12:42:27','<p><strong>Permanent records</strong>&nbsp;are physical records that indicate&nbsp;</p>',1,1,5,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (30,'<p>Which of the following are examples of preference assessments that behavior analysts might use to determine lists of appetitive stimuli?</p>','2017-07-06 14:53:27','<p>A&nbsp;<strong>multiple stimulus without replacement (MSWO)</strong>&nbsp;is a preference assessment commonly used by analysts to generate hierarchies of preferences for individuals whose preferences may be unclear or difficult to determine.</p>

<p>An array of items is presented (usually 5 - 8) and the student will be asked to&nbsp;<em>choose one</em>. The therapist will record the item picked, allow the student to engage with that item, then remove it for the remainder of the assessment. These steps are repeated until every item has had a chance to be selected or the student has not selected an item on 2 or more consecutive trials.</p>

<p>The resulting list may look like this:</p>

<ol>
	<li>Baseball</li>
	<li>Bubbles</li>
	<li>Barney Cartoon</li>
	<li>Cars 3 Movie (YouTube clips)</li>
	<li>Rice Bin</li>
	<li>No Selection</li>
	<li>No Selection - test discontinued</li>
</ol>

<p>This type of assessment may be conducted several times, generating data on how often a choice may be picked and in what order. This allows us to generate ranked lists of the average preference of items in relation to other items.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>',1,1,8,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (31,'<blockquote>
<p>Mrs. Susan has two sons, Tim and Tom, who are both identical twins. The boys rough house and fist-fight a lot, and she does not know what to do with them. Soon, Mrs. Susan makes a new rule: every time the boys rough house or fist-fight, if she catches them,&nbsp;she will take away 15 minutes from their video game play time that day.</p>

<p>After a few days, she notices that the boys stop fist-fighting and rough housing (at least, around her).</p>
</blockquote>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>What type of consequence is the&nbsp;<u><strong>removal</strong> of video game time</u> which Mrs. Susan observes <strong>decreases</strong> the behavior of <u>fist-fighting or rough-housing</u> over time?</p>','2017-07-06 18:53:55','<p><strong>Negative punishment</strong>&nbsp;is the removal of a preferred stimulus contingent on a specific behavior which causes that specific behavior to decrease over time.</p>

<p>In this case, we are&nbsp;<u>removing</u>&nbsp;a stimulus - therefore, we know this consequence is&nbsp;<strong>negative&nbsp;</strong>(by definition - negative just means &quot;Removes a stimulus&quot;). Since the behavior decreases over time, we know the consequence must be&nbsp;<strong>punishment</strong>, too. This means the consequence must be&nbsp;<strong>negative punishment</strong>!</p>',1,1,13,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (32,'<p>Skinner described <strong>Verbal Behavior&nbsp;</strong>according to _________ over _________.</p>','2017-08-06 23:44:13','<p>Skinner described verbal behavior in terms of the&nbsp;<u>function</u>&nbsp;of the behavior over the&nbsp;<u>form</u> (aka, topography)&nbsp;of the behavior.</p>',1,1,24,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (33,'<p>An <strong>S<sup>D</sup></strong> can be best described as a...</p>','2017-12-29 18:40:51','<p>An S<sup>D</sup>&nbsp;is an extra antecedent stimulus that correlates with the availability of reinforcement. S<sup>D</sup>&nbsp;stands for &quot;discriminative stimulus.&quot;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>For example, if you were driving along the highway and saw a sign for a gas station, that sign would indicate that reinforcement was available for the behavior&nbsp;of driving to the gas station + purchasing gas (the reinforcement, in that case, would be having a full tank of gas).</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Another example of an S<sup>D</sup>&nbsp;could be the hot n&#39; fresh sign outside of a donut shop - when you see the sign lit up, it indicates to you that a particular reinforcer - hot n&#39; fresh donuts - are available should you go inside and attempt to purchase them.</p>',1,1,17,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (34,'<p><strong>What type of data collection does this describe?</strong></p>

<blockquote>
<p>Samantha collected the total number of times Edward slapped the table and said &quot;Well how about that!&quot; during Thanksgiving dinner.</p>
</blockquote>','2018-04-12 01:56:19','<p><strong>Frequency</strong>&nbsp;is a&nbsp;<u>continuous</u>&nbsp;type of data collection which records the total count of discrete instances of behavior.</p>

<p>You might count any number of things - such as the frequency of utterances of the word &quot;aardvark&quot; in class, or the number of times someone gets an A+ on their math exam.</p>',2,1,3,4);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (35,'<p>What type of data collection does this describe?</p>

<blockquote>
<p>Sarah collected the duration of time it took her <strong>father</strong> to finish doing the dishes after dinner, measuring from the onset of washing (putting soap on the first dish) till the offset of washing (drying and putting away the last dish).</p>

<p><em>Sarah should have helped her father do the dishes, by the way.</em></p>
</blockquote>','2018-04-19 03:51:57','<p><strong>Frequency</strong>&nbsp;is a&nbsp;<u>continuous</u>&nbsp;type of data collection which records the total length of time it takes for a behavior&nbsp;to begin and end.</p>

<p style="margin-left:40px">The <u>onset</u>&nbsp;refers to when the duration formally begins.</p>

<p style="margin-left:40px">The&nbsp;<u>offset</u>&nbsp;refers to when the duration formally ends.</p>',2,1,3,4);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (36,'<p>What type of data collection does this describe?</p>

<blockquote>
<p>Samantha collected the total number of times&nbsp;Edward slapped the table over three separate 1 hour observation periods.</p>

<p>Afterwards, she calculated the total number of times Edward slapped the table per hour.</p>
</blockquote>','2018-04-19 04:06:56','<p><strong>Rate</strong>&nbsp;is a&nbsp;<u>continuous</u>&nbsp;type of data collection which records the total count of discrete instances of behavior&nbsp;<strong>OVER SOME UNIT OF TIME.</strong></p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Rate can be compared when the length of the observation might vary, while Frequency can not be.</p>',2,1,3,4);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (37,'<p>What is one of the advantages of <strong>rate</strong> data collection?</p>','2018-04-22 17:23:14','<p>Rate measurements can be directly compared across time periods that aren&#39;t the same in length, as they describe a ratio of events per unit time. When the unit of time is the same, the values can be compared.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h2 style="font-style:italic"><u><span style="font-size:16px"><strong>Need an example?</strong></span></u></h2>

<p>Let&#39;s compare rate to frequency and see if that helps!</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Let&#39;s imagine that we have a small child who comes to a clinic for behavioral therapy twice a week. Without telling you anything else, I simply present to you the following data:</p>

<ul>
	<li><strong>Monday:</strong>&nbsp;150 episodes of aggression</li>
	<li><strong>Tuesday:</strong>&nbsp;200 episodes of aggression</li>
	<li><strong>Wednesday:</strong>&nbsp;200 episodes of aggression</li>
</ul>

<p>Just looking at that data, we&#39;d say Tuesday &amp; Wednesday weren&#39;t&nbsp;very good days. We&#39;d conclude that there was an increasing trend in the behavior (things are getting worse) just on those three data points!</p>

<p>However, let&#39;s expand our scenario a little bit. Let&#39;s say that our client&#39;s schedule is not the same on those three days, and it looks something like this:</p>

<ul>
	<li><strong>Monday:</strong>&nbsp;10:00am - 12:00pm</li>
	<li><strong>Tuesday:</strong>&nbsp;12:00pm - 5:00pm</li>
	<li><strong>Wednesday:</strong>&nbsp;10:00pm - 6:00pm</li>
</ul>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Now let&#39;s compare that data, one more time:</strong></p>

<table border="1" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; border:1px solid black; width:500px">
	<tbody>
		<tr>
			<td style="background-color:#6699ff; text-align:center; vertical-align:middle; width:33%"><span style="color:#ffffff"><strong>Day</strong></span></td>
			<td style="background-color:#6699ff; text-align:center; vertical-align:middle; width:33%"><span style="color:#ffffff"><strong>Frequency</strong></span></td>
			<td style="background-color:#6699ff; text-align:center; vertical-align:middle; width:33%"><span style="color:#ffffff"><strong>Rate</strong></span></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style="text-align:center">Monday</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">150</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">75 / hour</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style="text-align:center">Tuesday</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">200</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">40 / hour</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style="text-align:center">Wednesday</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">200</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">25 / hour</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody>
</table>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>From this example, we can see that rate can be pretty misleading!&nbsp;<strong>Changing the unit of measure changes our analysis of the situation!</strong>&nbsp;The behavior appears to be&nbsp;<em>increasing&nbsp;</em>when described as a <u>frequency</u> measure, but is definitely&nbsp;<em>decreasing</em>&nbsp;when described as a <u>rate</u> measure!</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Moral of the story?</strong>&nbsp;Be very careful when selecting a data type - all things considered, it&#39;s usually best to use rate when continuously tracking the occurrence of discrete behaviors for the simple reason that it allows you to more effectively compare behavior at different points in time.</p>',2,1,3,4);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (38,'<p>The onset to start recording the length of time a behavior takes - specifically, <em>crying (with or without tears) for longer than 10 seconds</em>. The offset is described as the <em>total absence of crying (with or without tears) for at least 10 seconds</em>.</p>

<p>What type of data collection does this most likely describe?</p>','2018-04-23 15:25:05','<p>Duration often has a specific&nbsp;<strong>onset</strong>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<strong>offset</strong>&nbsp;-- this refers to when a behavior starts, and when it stops -- basically, instructions when to start and stop the timer! This helps ensure consistency between data collectors.</p>

<p>Therefore, the answer to this question is...&nbsp;<strong>duration!</strong></p>',2,1,3,4);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (39,'<p><span style="font-size:16px"><strong>Which of the following graphs most clearly demonstrates a ACCELERATING TREND?</strong></span></p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Graph #1:</strong></p>

<p><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/ySOv95X.png" style="height:160px; width:250px" /></p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Graph #2:</strong></p>

<p><img alt="" src="https://imgur.com/3uhTZHV.png" style="height:142px; width:250px" /></p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Graph #3:</strong></p>

<p><img alt="" src="https://imgur.com/0I1q55K.png" style="height:146px; width:251px" /></p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Graph #4:</strong></p>

<p><img alt="" src="https://imgur.com/qNULsck.png" style="height:147px; width:250px" /></p>','2018-04-23 21:46:44','<p>An <strong>accelerating trend</strong> refers to an overall <strong>increase</strong> in responding, which will be reflected by an&nbsp;<strong>increased&nbsp;value</strong> being recorded on the Y axis (dependent variable) on the most recent data points.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>An example of a <strong>accelerating trend graph</strong> might look like this:</p>

<p><img alt="" src="https://imgur.com/0I1q55K.png" style="height:295px; width:500px" /></p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>An example of a <strong>decelerating trend graph</strong> might look like this:</p>

<p><img alt="" src="https://imgur.com/qNULsck.png" style="height:295px; width:500px" /></p>',2,1,6,4);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (40,'<p><strong>DISCONTINUOUS</strong> data collection records a&nbsp;<strong>sample</strong>&nbsp;of behavior, not an exact record of each instance of behavior.</p>

<p>Of the following, which are examples of discontinuous data collection?</p>','2018-04-25 03:03:55','<p>The following are common types of&nbsp;<strong>DISCONTINUOUS&nbsp;</strong>data collection:</p>

<p style="margin-left:40px"><strong>1. Momentary Time Sampling</strong> - recording data (YES or NO) regarding the occurrence of a behavior at a specific moment in time. This means that if the behavior was occurring for the entirety of the interval, but just happened to briefly stop at the point in time in which we observe the behavior, we might still mark &#39;no.&#39; This is one of the obvious drawbacks of this data collection scheme. One of the up-sides is that it&#39;s relatively resource unintensive - a single data collector could easily take data on many&nbsp;individuals simultaneously without becoming too overloaded.</p>

<p style="margin-left:40px"><strong>2. Partial Interval Recording -&nbsp;</strong>recording data (YES or NO) if the behavior occurs&nbsp;<u>for any part</u>&nbsp;of a given interval. For example, if the behavior occurs for 1 second or for the entire interval, you would still score it as a single &quot;yes&quot; for that interval. As a result, this type of recording tends to over-estimate behavior, which may be a good thing, depending on what you&#39;re trying to measure. For example, if you&#39;re teaching someone not to bite their teachers, even 1 second of biting could be pretty painful and disruptive. Therefore, you&#39;d be happy with overestimation as it would help guide treatment decisions in the right direction.</p>

<p style="margin-left:40px"><strong>3. Whole Interval Recording -&nbsp;</strong>recording data (YES or NO) if the behavior occurs&nbsp;<u>for the ENTIRETY</u>&nbsp;of an observation interval. For example, if the behavior occurs for 59&nbsp;seconds out of a 60 second observation interval, you would not score that interval! That seems pretty arbitrary, but it has it&#39;s benefits - imagine a scenario where you are attempting to take data on many learners who are supposed to be working on independent work. These same learners must raise their hand if they&#39;d like to get up from their table work. You could easily task a single teacher with taking WIR data on 5 or even 10 kids, and if you&#39;re interested in seeing an increase in their in-seat, on-task behavior, this would be a conservative measure of those behaviors -- a graph with a score of 100% would truly represent mastery, as even a single second of out-of-seat behavior would cost them an entire interval&#39;s score!</p>',2,1,4,4);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (41,'<p>Select the best&nbsp;<strong>definition</strong>&nbsp;for differential reinforcement, from the choices below:</p>','2018-04-26 03:15:14','<p>Differential reinforcement involves reinforcing members of one response class on a more favorable (for the behaver) schedule of reinforcement while withholding (or providing saliently less favorable) reinforcement to other members of other response class(es).</p>',1,1,26,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (42,'<p><strong>Satiation</strong> is a term that refers to what?</p>','2018-04-26 03:23:13','<p><strong>Satiation</strong> refers to the abolishing operation on the value of a specific stimulus created by over-exposure to that stimulus.</p>

<p>For example, having eaten a lot of food abolishes the value of food as a reinforcer.</p>

<p>One interesting aspect of &quot;generalized&quot; conditioned reinforcers --&nbsp;such as money&nbsp;-- is that no &quot;quantity&quot; of money is often enough to cause satiation earning it. Humans frequently exhaust themselves trying to earn money prior to reaching some point where they&#39;ve &quot;earned enough.&quot; This applies to other types of generalized reinforcers as well, such as praise and prestige.</p>',1,1,25,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (43,'<p>Which of the following is something that is true about the&nbsp;<strong>BCaBA</strong>&nbsp;(assistant analyst) certification?</p>','2018-04-26 03:27:05','<p>Per the BACB&#39;s website (<a href="https://www.bacb.com/bcaba/">link</a>):</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<blockquote>
<p>The Board Certified Assistant Behavior Analyst<sup>&reg;</sup>&nbsp;(BCaBA<sup>&reg;</sup>) is an undergraduate-level certification in behavior analysis. Professionals who are certified at the BCaBA level may not practice independently, but must be supervised by someone certified at the BCBA/BCBA-D level. In addition, BCaBAs can supervise the work of Registered Behavior Technicians, and others who implement behavior-analytic interventions.</p>
</blockquote>',1,1,34,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (44,'<p>Which of the following examples below is an example&nbsp;of a&nbsp;<strong>VARIABLE RATIO&nbsp;</strong>schedule of reinforcement?</p>','2018-04-26 03:32:28','<p>A variable ratio schedule of reinforcement describes an unpredictable ratio of responses prior to the delivery of a reinforcing stimulus.</p>

<p>A classic example is the lottery or gambvling - an unpredictable number of responses produces the reinforcing outcome. You could win the lotto on your first play, or on your 10,000th. It is highly random.</p>

<p>Not all schedules of reinforcement need to be so thin (in other words, inprobable). In applied behavior analysis, the ratio might be as simple as &quot;an&nbsp;average of 2 responses producing&nbsp;the reinforcer.&quot; This type of schedule is preferred when frequent responding is desired.</p>',1,1,13,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (45,'<p>Which of the following is an example of <strong>MASS TRIALS?</strong></p>','2018-04-26 03:37:05','<p><strong>Mass trials</strong>&nbsp;involve the repeated presentation of the same SD (discriminative stimulus) with prompting provided if needed to evoke a specific response. This is frequently done to promote the acquistion of a condition discrimination by repeated exposure to a reinforcing contingency.</p>',1,1,14,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (46,'<p>Which of the following are examples of <strong>verbal behavior?</strong></p>','2018-04-26 03:39:48','<p><strong>Verbal behavior</strong> is defined as the following:</p>

<ol>
	<li>Interaction between a communicator (doesn&#39;t have to be vocal) and an audience.</li>
	<li>The audience reinforcers the behavior of the communicator</li>
	<li>The function is of prime concern - the topography is secondary.</li>
</ol>',1,1,25,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (47,'<p>What are the four&nbsp;functions of behavior?</p>','2018-04-26 03:43:02','<p>The four functions of behavior (in layman&rsquo;s terms - <em>analysts may prefer to use more technical terms, such as social / automatically mediated, positive / negative, reinforcement / punishment</em>)&nbsp;are the following:</p>

<ul>
	<li><strong>Escape / Avoidance --&nbsp;</strong>delaying or avoiding entirely a non-preferred stimulus</li>
	<li><strong>Automatic Reinforcement (&quot;sensory&quot;) --&nbsp;</strong>behaviors that produce their own outcome without interaction of another person, such as drinking from a cup, reading a book, or scratching an itch</li>
	<li><strong>Attention --&nbsp;</strong>receiving interaction or joint activity from another person</li>
	<li><strong>Tangible --&nbsp;</strong>receiving items from another person</li>
</ul>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>It may help to remember <strong>S.E.A.T.</strong> - sensory, escape, access, and tangible!</p>',1,1,24,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (48,'<p>What does&nbsp;<strong>response latency</strong> refer to?</p>','2018-04-26 03:44:54','<p><strong>Response latency</strong> refers to the delay between a specific sitmulus and a response.</p>',1,1,3,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (49,'<p>When we refer to the&nbsp;<strong>validity</strong>&nbsp;of a measurement system, we are referring to what?</p>','2018-05-13 15:27:35','<p>Data are considered&nbsp;<strong>valid</strong>&nbsp;when the data are directly related to the phenomena being studied and the reason(s) for recording those data in the first place!</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>For example, was a relevant dimension of the behavior selected for data collection and analysis? For example, if you were working with an individual who frequently elopes into busy intersections, a 99% reduction in elopement might look good on paper, but there&#39;s still a chance of the individual being struck by a car. However, if you are working on improving an individuals ability to stay on task during math class, a 99% increase would be substantial. This difference is usually described as the&nbsp;<strong>social validity</strong> of a measure.</p>',2,1,2,4);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (50,'<p>What does <em><strong>onset</strong></em>&nbsp;refer to?</p>','2018-05-13 15:54:34','<p><strong>Onset&nbsp;</strong>and&nbsp;<strong>Offset</strong>&nbsp;are two terms used to refer to when to start and stop data collection for a given behavior.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>For example:</strong></p>

<p style="margin-left:40px">&nbsp;An &quot;episode&quot; of aggression might include a variety of aggressive acts, such as biting, kicking, and pinching. To make data collection easier - and allow a therapist to focus on protecting themselves and their client from harm as opposed to taking data! - we might first objectively define aggression <em>and then</em>&nbsp;use episodes of aggression&nbsp;defined as &quot;onset&nbsp;beginning with the first aggressive act, and an offset following a period of calm of at least 5 seconds without any aggressive behavior.&quot;</p>

<p style="margin-left:40px">Of course, this won&#39;t give us as precise a measure as we might like, but it can be useful. Some additional considerations might include a concern that episode count might decrease, but the length of episodes might increase or remain higher than desired, which may threaten the&nbsp;<strong>social validity</strong>&nbsp;of this measure.</p>',2,1,3,4);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (51,'<p>What does&nbsp;<strong>reliability</strong>&nbsp;of a measurement system refer to?</p>','2018-05-13 16:03:01','<p><strong>Reliability</strong>&nbsp;refers to the extent at which a measure produces the same value upon repeated testing. For example, if you use a thermometer to measure a child&#39;s temperature, a&nbsp;<strong>reliable</strong>&nbsp;thermometer would produce the same measurement (temperature) every time you used it.</p>

<p>Now, that doesn&#39;t necessarily mean the measure is correct - the thermometer could, for example, reliably say &quot;101 degrees Fahrenheit&quot; when the reality is the child has a normal temperature. That may be great for a kid looking for an excuse to skip math class, but not so great for a school nurse who&#39;s thermometer is not able to identify the&nbsp;<strong>true value</strong>&nbsp;for the child&#39;s temperature.</p>',2,1,2,4);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (52,'<p>Based on the data displayed on the graph below, what is the likely function of the client&#39;s problem behavior?</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><a href="https://imgur.com/efoyn4Y"><img alt="" src="https://imgur.com/efoyn4Y.png" style="border:1px solid black; height:364px; margin:0 auto 0 auto; width:500px" /></a></p>','2018-05-13 23:59:01','<p>In the graph displayed above, the client&#39;s behavior appears most elevated in the <strong>attention condition.</strong> There is a clear increase in trend, which sharply drops-off when the client is exposed to other test conditions.&nbsp;</p>',3,1,24,5);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (53,'<p>Based on the data displayed on the graph below, what is the likely function of the client&#39;s problem behavior?</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><a href="https://imgur.com/efoyn4Y"><img alt="" src="https://imgur.com/eTn2xEg.png" style="border:1px solid black; height:364px; margin:0 auto 0 auto; width:500px" /></a></p>','2018-05-14 00:35:27','<p>In the graph displayed above, the client&#39;s behavior appears most elevated in the <strong>tangible condition.</strong> There is a clear increase in trend of problem behavior in the <strong>tangible condition</strong>, but not in any of the other test-conditions.&nbsp;</p>

<p><em>Note:</em>&nbsp;be careful of iatrogenic effects when conducting functional assessments with tangibles. <strong>Iatrogenic</strong> means &quot;<em>caused by the [medical] assessment</em>&quot; and it&#39;s important to consider that providing a positive reinforcer contingent upon problem behavior may simply create a new function for that problem behavior! So, tread lightly when using tangible as test conditions!</p>',3,1,24,5);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (54,'<p>Based on the data displayed on the graph below, what is the likely function of the client&#39;s problem behavior?</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><a href="https://imgur.com/efoyn4Y"><img alt="" src="https://imgur.com/TpdW1Ip.png" style="border:1px solid black; height:364px; margin:0 auto 0 auto; width:500px" /></a></p>','2018-05-14 01:33:24','<p>In the graph displayed above, the client&#39;s behavior appears <strong>undifferentiated</strong>&nbsp;- that is to say, based off these test results, it&#39;s not possible to clearly distinguish one function over another. Session 4 (tangible) appears elevated in relation to the other sessions, but it is likely an&nbsp;<strong>outlier</strong>&nbsp;as it is the only point in the data set higher than 25 and the remaining tangible test conditions fall in line with the average level of the other test conditions.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>',3,1,24,5);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (55,'<p>Based on the data displayed on the graph below, what is the likely function of the client&#39;s problem behavior?</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><a href="https://imgur.com/Lzuihkc.png"><img alt="" src="https://imgur.com/Lzuihkc.png" style="border:1px solid black; height:364px; margin:0 auto 0 auto; width:500px" /></a></p>','2018-05-14 01:35:19','<p>In the graph displayed above, the client&#39;s behavior appears to be under the control of&nbsp;<strong>escape (from demand)</strong>. The response rate in the other conditions is fairly low, but increases steadily over time when exposed to the <strong>demand</strong> condition.</p>',3,1,24,5);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (56,'<p>Which of the following is the name for the type of&nbsp;<strong>preference assessment</strong>&nbsp;where the individual is offerred an array of likely preferred items (typically 5 - 7). As each item is selected, <u>it is removed from subsequent presentations</u> of the array until the learner has selected each item from the array.</p>','2018-05-15 02:35:20','<p>A&nbsp;<strong>multiple stimulus without replacement (MSWO - yes, I know, the acronym MSWO is missing the &quot;r&quot; so that&#39;s confusing!)</strong>&nbsp;preference assessment involves the presentation of typically 5 - 7 items at a time to determine which items are the most preferred and create a hierarchy of those items. Since the items are not &quot;replaced&quot;, when the item is selected, it&#39;s gone for the remainder of that assessment, so typically the highest value items are selected first. This assessment is often repeated several times to determine the average &quot;rank&quot; of each item in the array.</p>

<p>It&#39;s best practice for behavior analysts to rotate the position of each item in the array&nbsp;to ensure that the individual is not just &quot;choosing the item on the right side&quot; (or exhibiting some other kind of position bias).</p>

<p>Food items are typically not intermixed with tangible items during preference assessments, as research suggests that some individuals may exhibit preference for food items over tangible items and skew results of such intermixed assessments.</p>',3,1,8,5);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (57,'<p>Which of the following is a&nbsp;<strong>preference assessment</strong>&nbsp;where the individual is systematically exposed to many&nbsp;stimuli <strong>in sets of two</strong> - this&nbsp;arrangement allows for each&nbsp;item to be&nbsp;presented an equal number of times, which enables us to create a &quot;preference hierarchy&quot; (i.e., how much each item is preferred / non-preferred).</p>','2018-05-15 02:41:31','<p>A&nbsp;<strong>paired choice</strong>&nbsp;preference assessment involves the presentation of 2 items at a time from a larger list (usually 7 - 12 items) to determine which items are the most preferred. Each item is presented in combination with every item on the list, so that the individual is given an opportunity to &quot;choose&quot; which item they like the most in a contest against every other item.</p>

<p>Often times, behavior analysts will ensure that the position (on the left, or on the right) of the various stimuli is evenly rotated to ensure that the individual is not just &quot;choosing the item on the right side&quot; (or exhibiting some other kind of position bias).</p>

<p>Food items are typically not intermixed with tangible items during preference assessments, as research suggests that some individuals may exhibit preference for food items over tangible items and skew results of such intermixed assessments.</p>',3,1,8,5);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (58,'<p>Which of the following is the name for the type of&nbsp;<strong>preference assessment</strong>&nbsp;where the individual is systematically exposed to an array of potentially preferred stimuli, and each time they select an item from the array,<strong> they are allowed</strong>&nbsp;to select that item again on any subsequent presentations of the array, until the analyst is able to differentiate one or more of the stimuli as the &quot;most preferred&quot; from the array?</p>','2018-05-15 02:46:58','<p>A&nbsp;<strong>multiple stimulus <u>with</u>&nbsp;replacement</strong>&nbsp;preference assessment involves the presentation of typically 5 - 7 items at a time to determine which items are the most preferred and allow you to identify what is the &quot;most valuable&quot; item(s) from the array. Typically, one item will stand out from it&#39;s peers in the array - such as a special toy, like a blankie, or the iPad, etc. - that the individual will choose each and every time they are given the option to. Knowing what this stimulus is on a day-to-day basis can make these types of preference assessments incredibly valuable, especially for learners who have difficulty communicating their choice.</p>

<p>It&#39;s best practice for behavior analysts to rotate the position of each item in the array&nbsp;to ensure that the individual is not just &quot;choosing the item on the right side&quot; (or exhibiting some other kind of position bias).</p>

<p>Food items are typically not intermixed with tangible items during preference assessments, as research suggests that some individuals may exhibit preference for food items over tangible items and skew results of such intermixed assessments.</p>',3,1,8,5);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (59,'<p>Which of the following is the name for the type of&nbsp;<strong>preference assessment</strong>&nbsp;where the individual is allowed to freely roam a room seeded with potentially preferred stimuli while the analyst records the duration of engagement with each item in the room, hoping to gather an understanding of what items, if any, the individual spends their time with when allowed to freely interact with them, and potentially create a hierarchy out of the amount of time they allocate their responding?</p>','2018-05-15 02:51:24','<p>A&nbsp;<strong>free operant</strong>&nbsp;preference assessment allows learners freedom to roam an area, such as a play room, and interact with any items in the room they find motivating. The <strong>duration of engagement&nbsp;</strong>is recorded for each item, allowing analysts to compare the amount of time the individual spent with each item, and therefore determine if one item was more &quot;valuable&quot; than another simply by comparing the quantity of time the individual allocated to interacting with one item(s) over other(s).</p>

<p>Typically, these rooms are &quot;seeded&quot; with likely high-preference items based off care-giver / parent / guardian report, which increases the likelihood of the assessment being successful at generating a hierarchy (or ranking) of preferred items.</p>

<p>Food items are typically not intermixed with tangible items during preference assessments, as research suggests that some individuals may exhibit preference for food items over tangible items and skew results of such intermixed assessments.</p>',3,1,8,5);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (60,'<p>A _____________ <strong>(fill in the blank)</strong> is a type of assessment that allows analysts to determine the &quot;why&quot; (or reinforcers) for a specific behavior by arranging test conditions which manipulate antecedents &amp; consequences&nbsp;in an alternating design to evoke (and reinforce) problem behavior. After the assessment, the test conditions are compared with the goal of discriminating what test condition evoked the most problem behavior (and is, therefore, likely a functional reinforcer for that problem behavior).</p>','2018-05-15 02:55:40','<p>A&nbsp;<strong>functional analysis</strong>&nbsp;is a type of functional assessment where consequences are manipulated in an&nbsp;<strong>alternating design</strong>&nbsp;to demonstrate which consequences are likely functional reinforcers for a given behavior.</p>

<p>It can be odd to conduct a functional analysis as the goal is unusual - from the onset, you are attempting to reinforce problem behavior. By testing multiple types of potential reinforcers, you identify what type of antecedents and consequences likely evoke and reinforce that problem behavior.</p>',3,1,10,5);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (61,'<p>A __________&nbsp;<strong>(fill in the blank)</strong>&nbsp;is a type of assessment where&nbsp;stimuli are presented to an individual in a systematic fashion&nbsp;with the overall&nbsp;goal of determining what, if any, of the stimuli are preferred by that individual - these &ldquo;preferred&rdquo; stimuli may be then&nbsp;used as reinforcers.</p>','2018-05-15 03:00:55','<p>A&nbsp;<strong>preference assessment</strong>&nbsp;allows us to determine what stimuli are (and are not) preferred by an individual, by measure of how much time they spend interacting with an item (or the frequency of times they choose that item from an array of other items).</p>

<p><strong>PLEASE NOTE:&nbsp;</strong>preference does not necessarily imply reinforcing value - for example, if you offerred me a plate with $1.00, a skittle, an M&amp;M, and a smiley face sticker on it, each time I would choose the $1.00. You might write down &quot;$1.00 is the most preferred item&quot; and then attempt to use it as a reinforcer for a variety of tasks. If one of the tasks was touching my nose, sure, I&#39;d be likely to find that $1.00 very reinforcing for that behavior. However, if you change the response requirement to &quot;mowing your massive front yard&quot; I am unlikely to find that $1.00 very reinforcing - my motivating operations will be changed by the response requirement, in this case! So keep that in mind when utilizing the results of your preferrence assessments (or look up&nbsp;<strong>reinforcer assessments</strong> in JABA).</p>',3,1,8,5);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (62,'<p>A therapist is working with a client with limited vocal laguage. This child is stacking blocks on a table. As he interacts with the blocks, the therapist periodically asks the client what color, shape, and comparative size the blocks are as the child plays.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>What type of teaching strategy is this?</p>','2018-05-19 22:34:29','<p><strong>Incidental teaching</strong>&nbsp;involves following the clients motivating operations and using those naturally occurring MOs to contrive opportunities to use language, functional skills, or engage in other behaviors of interest.</p>',4,1,15,6);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (63,'<p>Which of the following is typically <u>NOT</u>&nbsp;included as an essential component in a skill acquisition plan?</p>','2018-05-19 23:31:55','<p>The following are example of essential components of a skill acquisition program:</p>

<ul>
	<li><strong>Materials</strong> - what items, if any, are needed to complete the program.</li>
	<li><strong>Long Term Goal</strong> (or, <em>Long Term Objective</em>) - typically achieved in a six to twelve month time frame, with a broad and&nbsp;general statement such as &ldquo;<em>student will read sight words at the 2nd grade level&rdquo; </em>or <em>&ldquo;student will be able to prepare, consume, and put away snack materials without going off task.&rdquo; </em>A long term goal (LTG)&nbsp;will generate several suitable short term goals, which allow you to focus treatment decisions and begin to identify discrete behaviors for that skill that might need to be taught.</li>
	<li><strong>Short Term Goal</strong> (or, <em>Short Term Objective</em>) - typically achieved on the time frame of a few weeks to a few months, short term goals are collections of specific related skills that support the long term goal. Continuing the example above with a long term goal of&nbsp;&ldquo;<em>student will read sight words at the 2nd grade level,&rdquo; </em>some examples of supporting short term goals could include identifying letters printed in a variety of fonts, mastering 50 sight words, and decoding unknown words using phonics.</li>
	<li><strong>Learn Unit </strong>- &ldquo;The learn unit consists of the inter-locking operants of instruction that incorporate particular student and teacher interactions that predict whether student behavior will be controlled by particular stimuli and setting events.&rdquo;&nbsp;<em>(Greer, 1994a). </em>This is a description, essentially, of how to teach (and respond to) the behavior of a learner. You will typically encounter this in the form of a written &ldquo;ABC&rdquo; (<em>antecedent</em>, <em>behavior, consequences) </em>for the skill being taught.
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Response Definition </strong>- Objective description of the target behavior</li>
		<li><strong>Antecedent - </strong>the MOs, SDs, and any other setup that needs to be arranged prior to the behavior occurring</li>
		<li><strong>Consequence - </strong>typically, the teacher/interventionists response, usually providing a specifically prescribed reinforcer or punisher differential to the &ldquo;correctness&rdquo; of the learner&rsquo;s response.</li>
	</ul>
	</li>
</ul>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><em>Sources:</em></p>

<p><u><strong>Long term goals and objectives:</strong></u></p>

<ul>
	<li>Schloss, P. J. &amp; Smith; J. A. (1998). Applied Behavioral Analysis in the Classroom (2nd ed.). Boston: Allyn &amp; Bacon.</li>
</ul>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong><u>The Learn Unit</u></strong></p>

<ul>
	<li>Greer, R. D., &amp; McDonough, S. H. (1999). Is the learn unit a fundamental measure of pedagogy?&nbsp;<em>The Behavior Analyst</em>,&nbsp;<em>22</em>(1), 5&ndash;16.</li>
</ul>',4,1,11,6);
