INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (67,'<p><strong>Stimulus transfer</strong> is the process of transferring stimulus ______ from one set of antecedent variables to another, typically using prompting and prompt fading.</p>','2018-05-19 23:49:04','<p>&ldquo;<strong>Stimulus control </strong>refers to a change in operant behavior that occurs when a particular type of stimulus (SD&nbsp;or S&Delta;) is presented. With an SD, the behavior occurs in the presence of that stimulus and does not occur in its absence. With an S&Delta;, the behavior does not occur in the presence of that stimulus. Stimulus control develops when a given response is repeatedly reinforced in the presence of a particular stimulus (SD) and not in its absence, or not in the presence of a different stimulus (S&Delta;). <strong>Transfer of stimulus control</strong> occurs when behavior initially evoked (controlled) by one SD&nbsp;comes under the control of a different SD.&rdquo;</p>

<p style="margin-left:40px">Bloh, C. (2008). Assessing Transfer of Stimulus Control Procedures Across Learners With Autism.&nbsp;<em>The Analysis of Verbal Behavior</em>,&nbsp;<em>24</em>(1), 87&ndash;101.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>',4,1,18,6);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (68,'<p><strong>Transfer of stimulus control</strong> occurs when a behavior evoked in the presence of an SD comes under the control of another _______ . <em>(Fill in the blank)</em></p>','2018-05-19 23:53:15','<p>&ldquo;<strong>Stimulus control</strong> refers to a change in operant behavior that occurs when a particular type of stimulus (SD&nbsp;or S&Delta;) is presented. With an SD, the behavior occurs in the presence of that stimulus and does not occur in its absence. With an S&Delta;, the behavior does not occur in the presence of that stimulus. Stimulus control develops when a given response is repeatedly reinforced in the presence of a particular stimulus (SD) and not in its absence, or not in the presence of a different stimulus (S&Delta;). <strong>Transfer of stimulus control</strong> occurs when behavior initially evoked (controlled) by one SD&nbsp;comes under the control of a different SD.&rdquo;</p>

<p style="margin-left:40px">Bloh, C. (2008). Assessing Transfer of Stimulus Control Procedures Across Learners With Autism.&nbsp;<em>The Analysis of Verbal Behavior</em>,&nbsp;<em>24</em>(1), 87&ndash;101.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>',4,1,19,6);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (69,'<p>A behavior tech is showing a car to a student. They were asked to use a stimulus transfer procedure to teach the client to mand for the car.</p>

<p>When the student is shown the car, the tech waits for 5 seconds before providing the echoic prompt&nbsp;&ldquo;car&rdquo;, pausing for 2 - 3 seconds to allow the student to repeat the echoic prompt.&nbsp;If the student says &ldquo;car,&rdquo; the are given the car; otherwise, after 3 repetitions of the echoic prompt (and brief delay), the client is just given the item. After several days of intense training, the client begins to produce the vocal mand &ldquo;car&rdquo; more reliably, the the behavior tech fades out the use of the echoic prompts altogether as the client begins to produce the mand independently and consistently.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>What type of stimulus transfer procedure is this?</strong></p>','2018-05-20 00:01:29','<p>The therapist is using an echoic model prompt in an attempt to teach a mand. The behavior is initially under the control of the MO for the item (in sight) plus the echoic prompt. As teaching progresses, the echoic prompt is faded out entirely and the learner is able to independently mand &ldquo;car.&rdquo; Therefore, this is an <strong>echoic-to-mand </strong>transfer procedure.</p>',4,1,19,6);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (70,'<p>A therapist is working with a client on tooth-brushing in a task-analyzed format. The therapist is teaching the entire set of steps in the task analysis, which means they are employing what method of task analysis training?</p>','2018-05-20 00:18:37','<p><strong>Total or Whole Task </strong>training refers to the teaching all&nbsp;of the steps in a task analysis and providing reinforcement differential to independence on the entire set of skills.</p>',4,1,16,6);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (71,'<p><strong>Position bias </strong>refers to what?</p>','2018-05-20 00:23:27','<p><strong>Position bias </strong>refers to responding that is under the control (undesirably) of the position of the item in an array. For example, if a learner is asked &ldquo;hand me the green&rdquo; card, and they typically always select the card to their right regardless of it&rsquo;s color, that would be&nbsp;an example of position biased responding.</p>',4,1,14,6);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (72,'<p>When planning a client&rsquo;s training to <strong>generalize</strong> a skill to other people, places, or settings, what should an analyst <em>NOT</em>&nbsp;do?</p>','2018-05-20 09:40:39','<p><strong>Train and hope </strong>was described by T.F Stokes and Donald Baer as:</p>

<blockquote>
<p>&ldquo;<em>After a behavior change is effected through manipulation of some response consequences, any existent generalization across responses, settings, experimenters, and time, is concurrently and/or subsequently documented or noted, but not actively pursued.&rdquo;</em></p>
</blockquote>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h2>What does this mean?</h2>

<p>Some analysts fall into the trap of simply &ldquo;hoping&rdquo; that generalization will occur without actively programming for it - as described in their original article, there are at least 7 suggested methods by which an analyst can actively promote generalization of a skill across time, people, and places.</p>

<ol>
	<li><strong>Sequential Modification -</strong>&nbsp;when transferring stimulus control from one setting to another, allow for small successive approximations from the initial comntrolling stimulus to progressively different variations of the stimulus until, eventually, the dimensions of the S<sup>D</sup>&nbsp;have been altered sufficiently and the terminal stimulus has effective control of the target behavior.&nbsp;</li>
	<li><strong>Introduce to Natural Maintaining Contingencies -</strong>&nbsp;plan to fade any artificially dense schedule of reinforcement towards the active schedule in the client&rsquo;s natural environment.</li>
	<li><strong>Train Sufficient Exemplars -</strong>&nbsp;introduce the learner to sufficient variants of the target stimuli such that reinforcement has been contacted for engaging in the response when a wide variety of non-critical elements of the S<sup>D</sup>&nbsp;/ relevant dimensions for stimulus transfer have been varied or removed - i.e., tacting &ldquo;bird&rdquo; when shown a variety of birds of different colors, shapes, sizes (all non-critical elements of the class of animal) whereas some features will likely be consistent across all exemplars (has wings, a beak, feathers, etc.)</li>
	<li><strong>Train Loosely - </strong>little or no effort is made to control (in an experimental / highly consistent manner) the presentation of the stimuli and the range of acceptable answers is broadened.</li>
	<li><strong>Use Indiscriminable Contingencies -</strong>&nbsp;during teaching, use or fade towards intermittent schedules of reinforcement to mirror the likely schedule(s) that will be encountered naturalistically. Additionally, if necessary,&nbsp;make it hard to determine when the behavior will contact reinforcement and when it will not, to promote responding even in contexts where reinforcement is not likely to occur.</li>
	<li><strong>Program Common Stimuli </strong>- plan to use stimuli that are relevant to the learner and will likely be encountered in the day-to-day natural environment. For example, if you are teaching the child tacts, teach them first things they see on their daily routine - their&nbsp;lunchbox, a doorknob, a car, etc.</li>
