INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (76,'<p>Food, sex, water, breathable air&nbsp;and any other stimuli that are necessary for life (homeostasis) are what types of _________ reinforcement?</p>','2018-05-20 15:43:56','<p><strong>Unconditioned Reinforcers&nbsp;</strong>are types of reinforcers that have phylogenetically reinforcing value - that is to say, their reinforcing value is derived from their direct influence on an organisms genetics - typically, this will be things like food, breathable air, sex, water, and some things that may be specific to the species examined, such as &ldquo;burrowing spaces&rdquo; for animals such as guinea pigs that may reflexivly&nbsp;seek shelter when loud startling noises are heard.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Conditioned Reinforcers - </strong>stimuli that are paired repeatedly with unconditioned reinforcers (food, water, shelter, etc.) may acquire reinforcing value themselves. Additionally, previously conditioned reinforcers (such as movie tickets, which can be exchanged for access to a movie theater) can be paired with a previously neutral (or even aversive) stimulus to alter it&rsquo;s value. For example, getting free movie tickets in exchange for donating blood was a strategy employed by the makers of the Saw horror movie franchise, and it was reinforcing enough to<a href="https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jigsaw_(2017_film)"> increase blood drive participation markedly</a>.</p>

<p>For example, money is typically used to purchase a wide variety of reinforcers by humans - infants, however, will find little reinforcing value from currency aside from, perhaps, oral or visual stimulation. As time goes on, they will experience reinforcement through the stimuli money Is exchanged for, such as movie tickets, bubble gum, cigarettes, and cars. Behaviors that produce money on various schedules of reinforcement -&nbsp;such as allowances, chore money, their first paying jobs, etc. - will subsequently condition those behaviors that earn money as reinforcing as well.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Ontogenic properties are properties of a stimulus that are learned. The phylogenetic properties of stimuli serve as the basis from which ontogenetic learning will evolve. A common criticism of behavior analysis is that behavior analysts ignore the impact of genetics - this is not true! Behavior analysts should know and understand the evolutionary, genetic root of respondent behaviors, and how those roots grow into the many operant behaviors exhibited by all organisms.</p>',3,1,13,5);
