INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (97,'<p>A <strong>behavior-altering</strong> effect of a motivating operation can be best described as a...</p>','2018-05-28 16:53:03','<h1><strong>What are Motivating Operations?</strong></h1>

<p><strong>Motivating Operations (MOs)</strong>&nbsp;are an environmental variable that have both an effect on the consequences for behavior, and the behavior itself. You&#39;ve known about MOs all your life - you just probably used the more common parlance of &quot;He likes ice cream,&quot; &quot;I don&#39;t like Taylor Swift&#39;s music,&quot;&nbsp;or &quot;I like to eat salsa.&quot; What you&#39;re talking about is the impact of a stimulus on your behavior, and you&#39;re sharing it so other people know that if they want to make themselves more reinforcing to you, they should have ice cream and salsa available when you come over, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=taylor+swift&amp;page=&amp;utm_source=opensearch">and leave Taylor Swift off the music playlist</a>.</p>

<h2>&nbsp;</h2>

<h2><strong>How do MOs work?</strong></h2>

<p>From a behaviorist&#39;s point of view, we must describe all stimuli in terms of the objective outcomes in terms of behavior change - this helps us avoid <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mentalism_(psychology)">mentalistic</a> descriptions which are outside the purvue of behavioral science.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Motivating operations&nbsp;<strong>(MOs)</strong>&nbsp;are linked to stimuli, and impact&nbsp;<u>the organism</u>&nbsp;in two ways:</p>

<p style="margin-left:40px"><strong>1.&nbsp; Value-altering effect</strong>: they modify (increase or decrease) the efficacy of a stimulus as a punisher or reinforcer</p>

<p style="margin-left:40px"><strong>2.&nbsp; Behavior-altering effect:</strong>&nbsp;they increase the frequency (increase or decrease) of a behavior that has been punished or reinforced by that stimulus.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>For example, the sight of an empty gas guage while driving down the highway will&nbsp;<u>increase</u>&nbsp;the effectiveness of behaviors that produce gasoline as reinforcers (value-altering: <u>increase</u>), and increase the momentary frequency of behaviors that produce gasoline (behavior-altering: <u>increase</u>).</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Other behaviors that will fill up your gas tank will also experience the same effect, proportional to their availability (as signaled by SDs) and their individual learning histories (of reinforcement, punishment). For example, maybe calling a roadside assistance service (such as <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Automobile_Association">AAA</a>) or <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hitchhiking">pulling over to the side of the road and sticking your thumb up</a>.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Conversely, the sight of a full gas guage while driving down the road will&nbsp;<u>decrease</u>&nbsp;the effectiveness of behaviors that produce gasoline as reinforcers (value-altering:&nbsp;<u>decrease</u>), and&nbsp;<u>decrease</u>&nbsp;the momentary frequency of behaviors that might produce gasoline (behavior-altering:&nbsp;<u>decrease</u>).</p>

<h2>&nbsp;</h2>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h2><strong>EOs vs. AOs</strong></h2>

<p>It can be helpful to describe MOs more specifically when the need arises:</p>

<ul>
	<li><strong>Establishing Operations (EOs)&nbsp;</strong>are motivating operations that&nbsp;<u>establish</u>&nbsp;(increase) the effectiveness of some stimulus as a reinforcer -- also&nbsp;<strong>establishing effect.</strong></li>
</ul>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<ul>
	<li><strong>Abolishing Operations (AOs)</strong>&nbsp;are motivating operations that <u>abolish</u>&nbsp;(decrease) the effectiveness of some stimulus as a reinforcer -- also&nbsp;<strong>abative effect.</strong></li>
</ul>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>',5,1,25,7);
