INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (103,'<p>The disruption of a previously reinforcing contingency, such that the functional reinforcer is no longer available, is referred to as?</p>','2018-05-30 03:09:29','<p><strong>Extinction</strong>&nbsp;is the process of disrupting a previous reinforcing relationship such that a behavior that&nbsp;<u>previously</u>&nbsp;produced a given reinforcer no longer produces that reinforcer.</p>

<p>Extinction typically results in an&nbsp;<u>extinction burst</u>&nbsp;- a temporary increase in responding, prior to a usually sudden drop-off in behavior - as well as&nbsp;&quot;<u>emotional responding</u>&quot;&nbsp;aka &quot;<u>novel responding</u>,&quot; which is the emergence of new topographies (or resurgence of previously extinguished behaviors that have produced the same functional reinforcer of the behavior currently on extinction).&nbsp;</p>',5,1,27,7);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (104,'<p>What type of <strong>differential reinforcement</strong> procedure involves the strengthening of a response that is physically impossible to perform simultaneous with some other, non-preferred response?</p>','2018-06-02 21:31:40','<p><strong>Differential Reinforcement of OTHER Behavior (DRO)</strong>&nbsp;is the provision of reinforcement contingent upon any / all behaviors&nbsp;<u>excluding</u>&nbsp;a specific behavior. For example, you might provide a reinforcer every 5 minutes as long as a client has not engaged in aggressive behavior (hitting, kicking, slapping).</p>

<p>DROs may inadvertently reinforce undesired behaviors.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Differential Reinforcement of ALTERNATIVE&nbsp;Behavior</strong> (<strong>DRA</strong>) is the provision of reinforcement contingent upon a specific behavior occurring. Typically, but not always, this is the same functional reinforcer as a behavior that might be simultaneously targeted for reduction.</p>

<p><em>Here&#39;s a link to an excellent video featuring <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PQE1RyFziv4&amp;t=1s">Dr. Timothy Vollmer discussing differential reinforcement of alternative behavior</a>, a research focus of his at his lab at the University of Florida.</em></p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Differential Reinforcement of HIGHER or LOWER Rates of Behavior</strong>&nbsp;(<strong>DRH&nbsp;/ DRL</strong>) are both procedures that depend on the inter-trial interval of behavior, which might be a little confusing just looking at the name alone (i.e., the whole&nbsp;<em>rate</em>&nbsp;part). Yes, you are trying to reduce the rate of behavior, however responses are only reinforced if a specific latency has occurred since the last response. Therefore, you&#39;re really just trying to increase / decrease the inter-trial interval (&quot;gap&quot;) between responses, which will, as a product, increase or decrease the rate, of course.&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Differential Reinforcement of INCOMPATIBLE Behavior (DRI)</strong>&nbsp;is a type of reinforcement procedure where a behavior incompatible with another response is placed on a schedule of reinforcement, whereas the opposing response is placed on extinction or&nbsp;a lower schedule of reinforcement.&nbsp;An example could be sitting in a chair vs. standing upright.</p>',5,1,26,7);
