INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (107,'<p>Tim, an RBT, is at the supermarket when he sees a client that he regularly works with. He excitedly greets his client and talks about their most recent therapy session. After he heads home, he realizes he did something wrong - what was it?</p>','2018-06-04 03:44:36','<p>The&nbsp;<strong>Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act</strong>&nbsp;has specific requirements for individuals who interact with&nbsp;<strong>Protect Health Information</strong>&nbsp;(PHI).&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Approaching a client in public and dicussing the details of a therapy session reveals two things: that the client is receiving therapy services, and may also reveal information about their diagnosis as well, both of which are protected elements of their medical record.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Tim would be advised to wait for the client to acknowledge him <strong>first</strong>, and then refrain from mentioning any details that might be classified as PHI. This can be very tricky thing to navigate in social contexts, such as a supermarket, mall, or community event, but is part and parcel of our obligation to protect the privacy of our clients as analysts.</p>',7,1,37,9);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (108,'<p>Samantha is an RBT who works at a behavioral health clinic. She has just been put in charge of sending out notices to clients regarding special events coming up each week, but was not trained very well. At the start of this week, she sends a mass communication to all clients letting them know about a special Autism awareness event coming up that Friday.&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>What did Samantha do wrong?</p>','2018-06-04 03:56:02','<p>The&nbsp;<strong>Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act</strong>&nbsp;has specific requirements for individuals who interact with&nbsp;<strong>Protect Health Information</strong>&nbsp;(PHI). Protected health information includes things like first / last names, medical records, etc. It is very important to handle this information carefully as the penalties imposed by the federal government are steep and there can be massive emotional / social consequences for clients who have had their data mishandled.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>If you are responsible for client communications, you must send emails to multiple clients using the BCC option to protect their privacy. If you are unsure how to do this, you should not be in charge of sending out mass emails at your company! It is against federal law (HIPPA) to send information (such as email addresses) from one client to another without their explicit consent.</p>',6,1,33,8);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (109,'<p>Sam is working with his supervisor and notices that his client is engaging in a novel form of self-injury. Unfortunately, his supervisor is not immediately available, so after resolving the situation to the best of his ability he attempts to notify his supervisor (via email).</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Which of the following would be an objective, behavioral email to Sam&#39;s supervisor?</p>','2018-06-04 04:05:47','<p>It is important that all communications with supervisors be <strong>OBJECTIVE</strong>. A good test for objectivity is to ascertain if the message meets the following criteria:</p>

<ol>
	<li>Is the message&nbsp;<strong>concise -</strong>&nbsp;is there a lot of unnecessary language / wordiness?</li>
	<li>Is the message&nbsp;<strong>clear -&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;is there any verbal ambiguity that could be resolved?</li>
	<li>Is the message&nbsp;<strong>complete -&nbsp;</strong>is there any information missing that is relevant to the issue at hand?</li>
</ol>

<p><strong>Additionally, it must be <u>BEHAVIORAL</u></strong>&nbsp;- there must specific behavior mentioned, avoiding emotional / mentalistic terminology, e.g. &quot;He got angry&quot; would be better phrased as &quot;He began to vocalize loudly for 30 - 45 seconds, repeatedly tapping his eye with his forefinger with enough pressure that damage could occur.&quot;</p>',6,1,31,8);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (110,'<p>Which of the following is an example of <strong>DISCONTINUOUS</strong> data collection?</p>','2018-06-26 14:07:14','<p><em>Remember: </em></p>

<ul>
	<li><strong>Discontinuos </strong>data collection refers to data that is taken of some sample of the behavior, not each and every instance of the behavior of interest.</li>
	<li><strong>Continuous</strong> data collection refers to data that is taken on each and every instance of behavior.</li>
</ul>

<p>The following are common types of&nbsp;<strong>DISCONTINUOUS&nbsp;</strong>data collection:</p>

<p style="margin-left:40px"><strong>1. Momentary Time Sampling</strong> - recording data (YES or NO) regarding the occurrence of a behavior at a specific moment in time. This means that if the behavior was occurring for the entirety of the interval, but just happened to briefly stop at the point in time in which we observe the behavior, we might still mark &#39;no.&#39; This is one of the obvious drawbacks of this data collection scheme. One of the up-sides is that it&#39;s relatively resource unintensive - a single data collector could easily take data on many&nbsp;individuals simultaneously without becoming too overloaded.</p>

<p style="margin-left:40px"><strong>2. Partial Interval Recording -&nbsp;</strong>recording data (YES or NO) if the behavior occurs&nbsp;<u>for any part</u>&nbsp;of a given interval. For example, if the behavior occurs for 1 second or for the entire interval, you would still score it as a single &quot;yes&quot; for that interval. As a result, this type of recording tends to over-estimate behavior, which may be a good thing, depending on what you&#39;re trying to measure. For example, if you&#39;re teaching someone not to bite their teachers, even 1 second of biting could be pretty painful and disruptive. Therefore, you&#39;d be happy with overestimation as it would help guide treatment decisions in the right direction.</p>

<p style="margin-left:40px"><strong>3. Whole Interval Recording -&nbsp;</strong>recording data (YES or NO) if the behavior occurs&nbsp;<u>for the ENTIRETY</u>&nbsp;of an observation interval. For example, if the behavior occurs for 59&nbsp;seconds out of a 60 second observation interval, you would not score that interval! That seems pretty arbitrary, but it has it&#39;s benefits - imagine a scenario where you are attempting to take data on many learners who are supposed to be working on independent work. These same learners must raise their hand if they&#39;d like to get up from their table work. You could easily task a single teacher with taking WIR data on 5 or even 10 kids, and if you&#39;re interested in seeing an increase in their in-seat, on-task behavior, this would be a conservative measure of those behaviors -- a graph with a score of 100% would truly represent mastery, as even a single second of out-of-seat behavior would cost them an entire interval&#39;s score!</p>',1,1,4,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (111,'<p>What is considered &quot;best practice&quot; when it comes to updating graphs and collecting data regarding behaviors measured during the day?</p>','2018-06-26 20:51:49','<h2>There are two basic rules about recording and charting data:</h2>

<ul>
	<li><strong>Always attempt to record data as soon as possible - if not as it occurs</strong>

	<ul>
		<li><span style="font-size:11px"><em>If this is not possible, you should consider changing your data collection to something more feasible!</em></span></li>
	</ul>
	</li>
</ul>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<ul>
	<li><strong>Charting (graphing) should be done either the same day, or at least once a week</strong>

	<ul>
		<li><span style="font-size:11px"><em>You can use online data collection tools, such as <a href="https://centralreach.com/">CentralReach</a> or <a href="https://www.datafinch.com/datacollection/features">Catalyst</a> (and that&#39;s just 2 among many great choices) to automatically graph your data as you collect it!</em></span></li>
	</ul>
	</li>
</ul>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>You should always make your best effort to record data as it happens. To do this most effectively, one can use <a href="https://smile.amazon.com/Ktrio-Counter-Mechanical-Clicker-Assorted/dp/B06XPD1YK3/ref=sr_1_14?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1530045930&amp;sr=8-14&amp;keywords=clicker">clickers</a>, an <a href="https://www.counteeapp.com/">app on a smart phone</a>, or some other mechanical / digital tool to store data for you. If you work with clients who exhibit high frequency (or dangerous) behaviors, it can be challenging to provide for their safety while maintaining their safety and your safety.</p>',1,1,6,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (112,'<p>Tilda finished her session after being supervised by her BCBA. During the session, she recorded data on a paper data collection sheet. While she was cleaning up, she spilled a cup of coffee all over her data sheet, making it completely illegible.</p>

<p><strong>What should Tilda do? Her company has strict policies regarding staff who fail to properly enter data at the end of a shift!</strong></p>','2018-06-26 21:08:48','<p>ABA is a science, and any science is nothing without accurate, reliable, and valid data collection. Falsifying data is never acceptable, although there may be times when estimations are acceptable. However, we should always communicate with our supervisors and colleagues when errors or mishaps occur that preclude accurate data collection, <strong>and no behavior analyst or registered behavior tech should ever falisify or misrepresent data collected during a session.</strong> Such an action would be a breach of our ethical code and bely the scientific foundation of our field.</p>

<p>Tilda should notify her supervisor of the issue and perhaps her company could consider switching to an electronic or mechanical data collection system (though those systems are not without their own weaknesses, such as power going out or a weak internet signal).</p>',1,1,6,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (113,'<p>When getting ready to collect behavior data, which of the following choices could be something you do to ensure you are well prepared and do a good job?</p>','2018-06-26 21:14:30','<h2>Generally, you should do both of the following to be prepared to collect data during your session:</h2>

<p style="margin-left:40px"><strong>Rule #1 Be aware of what you are taking data on</strong></p>

<ul>
	<li style="margin-left: 40px;">What are your specific behaviors of interest? What are their response definitions?</li>
	<li style="margin-left: 40px;">What phases are each of your specific behaviors of interest in? (baseline, intervention, etc.)</li>
</ul>

<p style="margin-left:40px">&nbsp;</p>

<p style="margin-left:40px"><strong>Rule #2 Have your data collection tools ready!</strong></p>

<ul>
	<li style="margin-left: 40px;">If you are tracking several behaviors that may occur at high rates and / or simultaneously, are you ready for that?</li>
	<li style="margin-left: 40px;">Do you need clickers, a pad and paper, etc. to be able to take notes on behavior during your session</li>
	<li style="margin-left: 40px;"><em>Your memory might be good, but you shouldn&#39;t rely on it</em></li>
</ul>

<p style="margin-left:40px">&nbsp;</p>

<p style="margin-left:40px">&nbsp;</p>',1,1,2,1);
