INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (115,'<p>Which of the following best describes <strong>momentary time sampling</strong> as a data collection method?</p>','2018-06-26 19:14:51','<p><em>Remember: </em></p>

<ul>
	<li><strong>Discontinuos </strong>data collection refers to data that is taken of some sample of the behavior, not each and every instance of the behavior of interest.</li>
	<li><strong>Continuous</strong> data collection refers to data that is taken on each and every instance of behavior.</li>
</ul>

<p>The following are common types of&nbsp;<strong>DISCONTINUOUS&nbsp;</strong>data collection:</p>

<p style="margin-left:40px"><strong>1. Momentary Time Sampling</strong> - recording data (YES or NO) regarding the occurrence of a behavior at a specific moment in time. This means that if the behavior was occurring for the entirety of the interval, but just happened to briefly stop at the point in time in which we observe the behavior, we might still mark &#39;no.&#39; This is one of the obvious drawbacks of this data collection scheme. One of the up-sides is that it&#39;s relatively resource unintensive - a single data collector could easily take data on many&nbsp;individuals simultaneously without becoming too overloaded.</p>

<p style="margin-left:40px"><strong>2. Partial Interval Recording -&nbsp;</strong>recording data (YES or NO) if the behavior occurs&nbsp;<u>for any part</u>&nbsp;of a given interval. For example, if the behavior occurs for 1 second or for the entire interval, you would still score it as a single &quot;yes&quot; for that interval. As a result, this type of recording tends to over-estimate behavior, which may be a good thing, depending on what you&#39;re trying to measure. For example, if you&#39;re teaching someone not to bite their teachers, even 1 second of biting could be pretty painful and disruptive. Therefore, you&#39;d be happy with overestimation as it would help guide treatment decisions in the right direction.</p>

<p style="margin-left:40px"><strong>3. Whole Interval Recording -&nbsp;</strong>recording data (YES or NO) if the behavior occurs&nbsp;<u>for the ENTIRETY</u>&nbsp;of an observation interval. For example, if the behavior occurs for 59&nbsp;seconds out of a 60 second observation interval, you would not score that interval! That seems pretty arbitrary, but it has it&#39;s benefits - imagine a scenario where you are attempting to take data on many learners who are supposed to be working on independent work. These same learners must raise their hand if they&#39;d like to get up from their table work. You could easily task a single teacher with taking WIR data on 5 or even 10 kids, and if you&#39;re interested in seeing an increase in their in-seat, on-task behavior, this would be a conservative measure of those behaviors -- a graph with a score of 100% would truly represent mastery, as even a single second of out-of-seat behavior would cost them an entire interval&#39;s score!</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>',1,1,4,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (116,'<p>When attempting to assess the function of a client&#39;s behavior, what is often considered the &quot;<strong>gold standard&quot;</strong>&nbsp;for experimentally identifying function?</p>','2018-06-27 12:53:12','<p>A&nbsp;<strong>functional analysis</strong>&nbsp;is an experimental methodology where an analyst repeatedly alters the contingencies in effect for a client&#39;s behavior in several test conditions with the goal of identifying which test condition is most reinforcing to the problem behavior. Since we know that a reinforcer increases a behavior over time, by repeatedly exposing behavior to putative reinforcers, we might expect to see an increase in that behavior over repeated exposures to the reinforcing test condition, and less or no change in the non-reinforcing test contingencies.</p>

<p>For example, some classic test contingenices are:</p>

<ul>
	<li><strong>Attention</strong>&nbsp;- an adult pre-occupeis themselves with some activity and &quot;ignores&quot; the child, and attention is provided only contingent upon the behavior of interest occurring</li>
	<li><strong>Escape&nbsp;</strong>- demands are placed (typically academic,&nbsp;but they can be any type of demands) and escape is provided contingent upon the behavior of interest occurring</li>
	<li><strong>Control -&nbsp;</strong>the client receives attention and free access to high-value reinforcers.&nbsp;No additional consequence for the behavior of interest.</li>
	<li><strong>Alone -&nbsp;</strong>the client is left &quot;alone&quot; (i.e., in a room which has a few low to medium preference activities for them to engage in) and an adult pre-occupies themself with some other activity. No additional consequence for the behavior of interest.</li>
</ul>

<p>There are many crucial ethical concerns to take into account when implementing a functional analysis, and informed consent of parents or caregivers is required. Sometimes, behaviors are too dangerous to conduct a functional analysis safely on - for instance, if a client engages in dangerous eye-gouging, exposing this behavior (eye-gouging) to reinforcement even briefly&nbsp;could be tremendously risky!</p>',1,1,10,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (117,'<p>Sally is an RBT working with a client named Jim. Jim tends to scream and bite his arm forcefully when presented with his token board, and sometimes when Sally opens up her laptop. Sally almost never opens up her laptop unless she&#39;s about to ask Jim to do some of his table work activities.</p>

<p><strong>What do you think the most likely function of Jim&#39;s behavior is?</strong></p>','2018-06-27 18:07:13','<p>The client&#39;s behavior has a history of occuring in the presence of demands, or signals - such as the opening of a laptop - that demand might be imminent. Therefore, it is likely that Jim&#39;s behavior is maintained by escape from demand.</p>

<p>Sally might consider taking ABC data on Jim&#39;s SIB to see if a consistent pattern emerges. It may also be useful to conduct a functional analysis to formally demonstrate a relationship between demand and SIB if feasible and safe.</p>',1,1,10,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (118,'<p>Which of the following <strong>environmental variables</strong> (antecedents) may have impacted a client&#39;s learning during that session?</p>','2018-07-29 04:41:53','<p>Many things can impact a client&#39;s ability to learn during a session - sleep, illness, family life problems, medication changes - these are all things the board specifically mentions in the RBT task list (E-01). It&#39;s important to note these events when you are made aware of them and, as needed, report them to your supervisor so that each event can be documented.</p>

<p>Some families may change their child&#39;s medication on a day-to-day basis (even without approval from a child&#39;s pediatrician) and this can severely alter their behavior, as you would imagine. Sometimes, it is helpful to have a prepared script for the onset of your session, asking basic info about homeostatic variables (sleep, food), any significant episodes of challenging behavior that day, changes in medication, or events in the household that may impact the child&#39;s performance in your session.</p>

<p>Always remember to be respectful, too - some information may be uncomfortable or difficult for your client&#39;s parents or guardians to share.</p>',6,1,29,8);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (119,'<p>When traveling between in-home therapy sessions, Todd accidentally forgot to store his client files and data sheets in the trunk of his car in the lockbox his company provides him. After a quick stop at a gas station, he found his car had been robbed, and his client files lost. Without knowing it, Todd has accidentally disclosed PHI and violated the Health Information Privacy &amp; Portability Act.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>What could Todd have done better to prevent this serious violation?</strong></p>','2018-07-29 04:47:50','<p>Your agency will be responsible for training you to the legal standard set by both local and federal law, per <a href="https://www.hhs.gov/hipaa/index.html">HIPPA</a>. Generally, it is a very bad idea to leave PHI out and accessible by non-authorized individuals as it not only exposes your client(s) to vulnerability in the form of identity theft &amp; violation of trust <em>but</em> it is also a serious crime!</p>',6,1,33,8);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (120,'<p>Which of the following way<strong> is a safe way to store data</strong> collected during a therapy session that may contain PHI (Personal Health Information)?</p>','2018-07-29 04:55:50','<p>Personal Health Information (PHI) - such as social security numbers, names, birthdays, diagnoses, treatment plan goals, etc. - must be kept in a locked (or password protected) file and comply with the standards set by the HIPPA act. From an RBT&#39;s perspective, you will likely be trained on a specific policy for your company, such as storing all client charts / data in binders in a lockable file cabinet or a locked room in your building.</p>

<p>When in doubt, contact your BCBA supervisor for specific advice on how to transport or store materials that contain PHI.</p>',6,1,33,8);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (121,'<p>While working with a client with irritable bowel syndrome, Cassidy exclaims &quot;ooooh-eeee! Somebody has the farts today!&quot; in a joking tone. Her client is pretty much non-verbal, so it&#39;s not a big deal - it&#39;s not very likely they&#39;ll feel embarassed by farting a lot, or having people comment on their farts.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>What&#39;s the most salient ethical dillema with Cassidy&#39;s behavior?</p>','2018-07-29 05:04:08','<p>As therapists, we must advocate for our clients. Part of that duty is respecting our client&#39;s dignity - providing them with the same privacy and respect we would want for ourselves. I imagine that Cassidy would be horrified if someone else loudly narrated any gastrointestinal distress she might experience throughout the day - and just because her client lacks the verbal skills necessary to indicate the punishing nature of her comments <em>does not necessarily mean those comments are not functioning as punishers!</em> The last thing we want to do, as therapists, is pair ourselves with punishment and become agents of aversiveness.</p>

<p>In addition, imagine how the parents might feel observing their child being treated this way. Would it nurture an environment of respect and trust? Probably not. Cassidy should discretely open a window but otherwise go about her day.</p>',7,1,34,9);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (122,'<p>Out of all of the options below, what is the RBT&#39;s role in the delivery of behavioral services (most closely)?</p>','2018-07-29 05:10:07','<p>The RBT primarily implements a behavior change plan, as designed by a certified analyst (BCaBA, BCBA). They are supervised regularly (5% of their direct hours) by a certified analyst to ensure competency. The RBT is on the front lines of behavioral service delivery - they work with clients, are trained to perform a wide variety of behavioral interventions, and collect (and may also graph) data on those interventions. The role of the RBT is pivotal when a BCBA or BCaBA is unavailable to work 1:1 with all of the clients on their caseload for all hours required in the service plan (which is often the case).</p>

<p><strong><em>Please Note:</em> RBTs - and BCaBAs, BCBAs, etc. - are not <em>licensed</em> - licensure is unique to each state in the U.S., and takes different shapes. Look up licensure in your state for more details. Some states don&#39;t offer licensure yet!</strong></p>

<p>RBTs may know their clients better than their supervisors, and in some respects, even their parents - some clients may work with a single therapist 20 - 30 hours a week, every week. That&#39;s a lot of 1-on-1 time!</p>

<p>To ensure quality service delivery, the RBT is supervised for 5% of all hours worked in a service delivery period, and must pass a competency exam as well as a supervised observational period.</p>

<p><strong>Wanna learn more? Read my earlier blog post for more on how folks can become an RBT:</strong></p>

<p><a href="https://aba.rocks/blog/so-you-want-to-become-an-rbt">https://aba.rocks/blog/so-you-want-to-become-an-rbt</a></p>',7,1,34,9);
