INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (127,'<p>Sam records the total amount of a behavior that occurs during his session. The session length is 2 hours. He divides the total count by the session length. What type of data is Sam calculating?</p>','2018-09-06 02:02:11','<p><strong>RATE </strong>(also known as frequency, <a href="https://smile.amazon.com/Applied-Behavior-Analysis-John-Cooper/dp/0134752554/ref=sr_1_2?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1536199238&amp;sr=8-2&amp;keywords=cooper+heron+heward">according to some people</a>) is the total count of a behavior over a unit of time. In behavior analysis, <u>RATE</u> = <u>FREQUENCY</u>, at least at the time of this current writing, and likely for quite a long time after this, too.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h1>Frequency vs. Rate vs. Count</h1>

<p><strong>Frequency</strong> and <strong>Rate</strong> are considered synonymous in behavior analysis, as crazy as that ight sound for those of you coming from backgrounds in other fields, such as mathematics or statistics.</p>

<p>In ABA, <strong>count</strong> is used to refer to the total number of occurrences of a behavior in a given period of time.</p>

<p><strong>Frequency</strong> and <strong>Rate</strong> both refer to a <u>count</u> of behaviors over a unit of time. This is critical in behavioral observation as two sessions may have different lengths, causing visual analysis of graphs to be confounded.</p>

<h2>An example, for illustration:</h2>

<h3><strong>COUNT</strong> Data for 1 Week:</h3>

<table align="center" border="1" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; width:250px">
	<caption>Table A</caption>
	<thead>
		<tr>
			<th scope="col" style="background-color:#6699ff; width:50%"><strong><span style="color:#ffffff">Session Day</span></strong></th>
			<th scope="col" style="background-color:#6699ff"><span style="color:#ffffff"><strong>COUNT Data</strong></span></th>
		</tr>
	</thead>
	<tbody>
		<tr>
			<td style="text-align:center">Monday</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">100</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style="text-align:center">Tuesday</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">110</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style="text-align:center">Wednesday</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">120</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style="text-align:center">Thursday</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">130</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style="text-align:center">Friday</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">140</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody>
</table>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h3><strong>RATE (aka, FREQUENCY)</strong> Data for 1 Week:</h3>

<table align="center" border="1" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; width:550px">
	<caption>Table B</caption>
	<thead>
		<tr>
			<th scope="col" style="background-color:#6699ff; width:20%"><strong><span style="color:#ffffff">Session Day</span></strong></th>
			<th scope="col" style="background-color:#6699ff; width:20%"><span style="color:#ffffff"><strong>COUNT Data</strong></span></th>
			<th scope="col" style="background-color:#6699ff; width:20%"><strong><span style="color:#ffffff">Session Length</span></strong></th>
			<th scope="col" style="background-color:#6699ff; width:20%"><span style="color:#ffffff">Calculation</span></th>
			<th scope="col" style="background-color:#6699ff; width:20%"><span style="color:#ffffff">FREQUENCY / RATE</span></th>
		</tr>
	</thead>
	<tbody>
		<tr>
			<td style="text-align:center">Monday</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">100</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">2 hours</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">100 / 2 hours</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">50 / hour</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style="text-align:center">Tuesday</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">110</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">3 hours</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">110 / 3 hours</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">37 / hour</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style="text-align:center">Wednesday</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">120</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">5 hours</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">120 / 5 hours</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">24 / hour</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style="text-align:center">Thursday</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">130</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">7 hours</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">130 / 7 hours</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">19 / hour</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style="text-align:center">Friday</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">140</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">8 hours</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">140 / 8 hours</td>
			<td style="text-align:center">18 / hour</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody>
</table>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Holy crap! That&#39;s a big difference in meaning. The <u>COUNT</u> data (table A) shows an <strong>increasing</strong> trend as the week goes on, and would be a cause for alarm if we were treating a problem behavior (or celebration if we were tracking some new, great skill).</p>

<p>However, when the COUNT is converted into FREQUENCY / RATE we see a different, more accurate story. The client&#39;s week gets longer and longer as the week goes on, resulting in a pretty substantial decrease as time goes on (a little more than 50% decrease). Whether that&#39;s good or bad, of course, depends on whatever the behavior is, but you can see how if your client has different sessions, comparing COUNT to RATE can be very misleading and influence your judgements improperly.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h2>Why do we have to use FREQUENCY differently than the rest of the world?</h2>

<p>Why does the United States &amp; England still not use the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metric_system">metric system</a>? <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pluto#IAU_classification">Why is pluto not a planet anymore</a>? Why is <a href="https://i.imgur.com/EV9Y7if.jpg">coffee better than tea</a>?</p>

<p>The answer is just simply culture and convention. If you read the <a href="https://smile.amazon.com/Applied-Behavior-Analysis-John-Cooper/dp/0134752554/ref=sr_1_2?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1536194837&amp;sr=8-2&amp;keywords=cooper+heron+heward">Cooper, Heron, and Heward</a> you will likely encounter teaching that will shape your behavior to be in line with FREQUENCY = RATE. However, other texts (see the citations below) disagree, and think behavior analysts should change their mind. Still others argue that frequency should be a synonym for rate, in line with the traditional definitions in other disciplines.</p>

<p>For now, it&#39;s probably best to just say &quot;RATE&quot; or &quot;COUNT&quot; and just forget about frequency altogether. Who would have thought that such a word could be such a <u>frequent</u> topic of debate? At any <u>rate</u>, good luck studying. Just <u>count</u> your blessings and move on.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h3><strong>Sources: </strong></h3>

<ul>
	<li>Cooper, John O., Heron, Timothy E.Heward, William L.. (2007) <em>Applied behavior analysis /</em>Upper Saddle River, N.J. : Pearson/Merrill-Prentice Hall</li>
	<li>Merbitz, C.T., Merbitz, N.H. &amp; Pennypacker, H.S. On Terms: Frequency and Rate in Applied Behavior Analysis <em>BEHAV ANALYST</em> (2016) 39: 333. https://doi.org/10.1007/s40614-015-0048-z</li>
	<li>Carr, James E., Nosik, Melissa R., Luke, Molli M. <em>Journal of Applied Behavior Analysis (2018) </em>51(2):436-439. doi: 10.1002/jaba.449</li>
</ul>',2,1,3,10);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (128,'<p>Which of the following is an adequate description of <u><strong>behavior</strong></u>, the nature phenomena that the study of behavior analysis focuses on?</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>','2018-09-27 01:32:56','<p><strong>Behavior</strong> is the physical action of an organism which involves the movement of some part of that organism - be that it&#39;s vocal chords, synapses, or limbs. Single celled organisms exhibit behavior, as do multicellular organisms. Big animals exhibit behavior (whales), and so do small animals (rodents).</p>

<p>Behavior always involves some temporal <u>locus</u> (it happens at some point in time), temporal <u>extent</u> (it happens for a specific duration in time), and <u>repeatability</u> (it can be <u>counted</u>).</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h3><u>Sources</u>:</h3>

<ul>
	<li>Cooper, John O., Heron, Timothy E.Heward, William L.. (2007) <em>Applied behavior analysis /</em>Upper Saddle River, N.J. : Pearson/Merrill-Prentice Hall</li>
</ul>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p style="margin-left:40px"><em><cite>&quot;</cite>[behavior is] the interaction of the muscles and the glands of a live organism and the enviornment [the organism exists in at this moment]&quot;</em></p>

<p style="margin-left:40px"><strong>- Jack Michael</strong></p>

<p style="margin-left:40px">&nbsp;</p>

<div style="margin-left:40px"><em><q>the behavior of an organism is that portion of an organism&rsquo;s interaction with the environment that is characterized by detectable displacement in space through time of some part of the organism and that results in measurable change in at least one aspect of the environment</q></em></div>

<div style="margin-left:40px">&nbsp;</div>

<div style="margin-left:40px"><strong>&ndash; Johnston &amp; Pennypacker (1980, 1993a)</strong></div>',3,1,7,11);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (129,'<p>What is a commonly used tool used by behavior analysts to identify an organism&#39;s <u>preference</u> value for a stimulus and the conditions under which that value might change when the contingency is modified (i.e., response effort, states of satiation / deprivation, or the schedule of reinforcement in effect)?</p>','2018-09-29 15:46:44','<p>A&nbsp;<strong>preference assessment</strong>&nbsp;allows us to determine what stimuli are (and are not) preferred by an individual, by measure of how much time they spend interacting with an item (or the frequency of times they choose that item from an array of other items).</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>PLEASE NOTE:&nbsp;</strong>preference for a stimulus (like M&amp;Ms) does not necessarily imply that it will reinforce a <u>contingent</u> behavior! Reinforcer assessments are conducted when you need to demonstrate that a stimulus does have reinforcing value - preference assessments are typically done first to identify likely reinforcers.</p>

<p>Some big things to remember:</p>

<ol>
	<li>Things that you generally &quot;prefer&quot; to interact with in your free time (like, say, watching Netflix, Hulu, whatever) aren&#39;t the only reinforcers for behavior. For example, chapstick is a reinforcer (for the behavior of putting chapstick on my lips) but only when the EO (chapped lips) is present. Similarly, kleenex is a reinforcer (for the behavior of reaching for / buying / kleenex) but only when the EO (a runny nose) is present.</li>
	<li>A powerful reinforcer (coffee, ice cream, netflix - I&#39;m a simple man) may not be sufficient when the contingency is too demanding. For example, I will engage in high rates of &quot;button pushing&quot; to contact those items (uber eats; typing on a keyboard to find a show to watch; etc.). I will not engage in high rates of &quot;mowing the lawn of a football sized field&quot; to contact those reinforcers, however.</li>
</ol>

<p style="margin-left:40px"><strong>E.G.</strong> You offer me a plate with $1.00, a skittle, an M&amp;M, and a smiley face sticker on it.</p>

<p style="margin-left:40px">Each time I would probably choose the $1.00. You might write down &quot;$1.00 is the most preferred item&quot; and then attempt to use it as a reinforcer for a variety of tasks. If one of the tasks was touching my nose, sure, I&#39;d be likely to find that $1.00 very reinforcing for that behavior. However, if you change the response requirement to &quot;building a brick house&quot; I am unlikely engage in very high rates of &quot;house-building&quot; behavior when the contingency is $1.00. My motivating operations will be changed by the response requirement, in this case! So keep that in mind when utilizing the results of your preferrence assessments.</p>

<p style="margin-left:40px">Similarly, states of <u>satiation</u> and <u>deprivation</u> may alter the value of stimuli. Tokens, such as a $1.00, can be exchange for a great many reinforcers, which makes it hard to satiate on them. However, if I was only offerred food items during a reinforcer assessment, and you determined my #1, #2, and #3 favorite foods accurately, and then tried to use those items as reinforcers after I ate a big meal at lunch... you&#39;d probably get a lot less behavior out of me. Motivation matters!</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>There are many types of <strong>preference assssments</strong> - here are the different types:</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h2><strong>Multiple Stimulus <u>WITH</u>&nbsp;Replacement</strong></h2>

<p>A&nbsp;<strong>multiple stimulus&nbsp;<u>with</u>&nbsp;replacement</strong>&nbsp;preference assessment involves the presentation of typically 5 - 7 items at a time to determine which items are the most preferred and allow you to identify what is the &quot;most valuable&quot; item(s) from the array. Typically, one item will stand out from it&#39;s peers in the array - such as a special toy, like a blankie, or the iPad, etc. - that the individual will choose each and every time they are given the option to. Knowing what this stimulus is on a day-to-day basis can make these types of preference assessments incredibly valuable, especially for learners who have difficulty communicating their choice.</p>

<p>It&#39;s best practice for behavior analysts to rotate the position of each item in the array&nbsp;to ensure that the individual is not just &quot;choosing the item on the right side&quot; (or exhibiting some other kind of position bias).</p>

<p>Food items are typically not intermixed with tangible items during preference assessments, as research suggests that some individuals may exhibit preference for food items over tangible items and skew results of such intermixed assessments.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h2><strong>Multiple Stimulus <u>WITHOUT</u> Replacement (MSWO):</strong></h2>

<p>A&nbsp;<strong>multiple stimulus without replacement (MSWO - yes, I know, the acronym MSWO is missing the &quot;r&quot; so that&#39;s confusing!)</strong>&nbsp;preference assessment involves the presentation of typically 5 - 7 items at a time to determine which items are the most preferred and create a hierarchy of those items. Since the items are not &quot;replaced&quot;, when the item is selected, it&#39;s gone for the remainder of that assessment, so typically the highest value items are selected first. This assessment is often repeated several times to determine the average &quot;rank&quot; of each item in the array.</p>

<p>It&#39;s best practice for behavior analysts to rotate the position of each item in the array&nbsp;to ensure that the individual is not just &quot;choosing the item on the right side&quot; (or exhibiting some other kind of position bias).</p>

<p>Food items are typically not intermixed with tangible items during preference assessments, as research suggests that some individuals may exhibit preference for food items over tangible items and skew results of such intermixed assessments.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h2><strong>Caregiver Report:</strong></h2>

<p>Sometimes, the most useful information regarding preference can be gleaned from those who know the individual best. Asking caregivers informally, or by following a formal checklist, such as the <strong>RAISD, </strong>can be useful at identifying preferred stimuli.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h2><strong>Paired Stimulus Preference Assessments:</strong></h2>

<p>A&nbsp;<strong>paired choice</strong>&nbsp;preference assessment involves the presentation of 2 items at a time from a larger list (usually 7 - 12 items) to determine which items are the most preferred. Each item is presented in combination with every item on the list, so that the individual is given an opportunity to &quot;choose&quot; which item they like the most in a contest against every other item.</p>

<p>Often times, behavior analysts will ensure that the position (on the left, or on the right) of the various stimuli is evenly rotated to ensure that the individual is not just &quot;choosing the item on the right side&quot; (or exhibiting some other kind of position bias).</p>

<p>Food items are typically not intermixed with tangible items during preference assessments, as research suggests that some individuals may exhibit preference for food items over tangible items and skew results of such intermixed assessments.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h2><strong>Free Operant Preference Assessments:</strong></h2>

<p>A&nbsp;<strong>free operant</strong>&nbsp;preference assessment allows learners freedom to roam an area, such as a play room, and interact with any items in the room they find motivating. The&nbsp;<strong>duration of engagement&nbsp;</strong>is recorded for each item, allowing analysts to compare the amount of time the individual spent with each item, and therefore determine if one item was more &quot;valuable&quot; than another simply by comparing the quantity of time the individual allocated to interacting with one item(s) over other(s).</p>

<p>Typically, these rooms are &quot;seeded&quot; with likely high-preference items based off care-giver / parent / guardian report, which increases the likelihood of the assessment being successful at generating a hierarchy (or ranking) of preferred items.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>',3,1,8,11);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (130,'<p>What is one way to identify a person&#39;s preferences without using trial-based or free-operant based procedures?</p>','2018-09-29 15:47:43','<p>A&nbsp;<strong>preference assessment</strong>&nbsp;allows us to determine what stimuli are (and are not) preferred by an individual, by measure of how much time they spend interacting with an item (or the frequency of times they choose that item from an array of other items).</p>

