<p>It&#39;s best practice for behavior analysts to rotate the position of each item in the array&nbsp;to ensure that the individual is not just &quot;choosing the item on the right side&quot; (or exhibiting some other kind of position bias).</p>

<p>Food items are typically not intermixed with tangible items during preference assessments, as research suggests that some individuals may exhibit preference for food items over tangible items and skew results of such intermixed assessments.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h3><strong>Multiple Stimulus <u>WITHOUT</u> Replacement (MSWO):</strong></h3>

<p>A&nbsp;<strong>multiple stimulus without replacement (MSWO - yes, I know, the acronym MSWO is missing the &quot;r&quot; so that&#39;s confusing!)</strong>&nbsp;preference assessment involves the presentation of typically 5 - 7 items at a time to determine which items are the most preferred and create a hierarchy of those items. Since the items are not &quot;replaced&quot;, when the item is selected, it&#39;s gone for the remainder of that assessment, so typically the highest value items are selected first. This assessment is often repeated several times to determine the average &quot;rank&quot; of each item in the array.</p>

<p>It&#39;s best practice for behavior analysts to rotate the position of each item in the array&nbsp;to ensure that the individual is not just &quot;choosing the item on the right side&quot; (or exhibiting some other kind of position bias).</p>

<p>Food items are typically not intermixed with tangible items during preference assessments, as research suggests that some individuals may exhibit preference for food items over tangible items and skew results of such intermixed assessments.</p>

<h2>&nbsp;</h2>

<h2>Asking the Individual:</h2>

<h3><strong>Caregiver Report:</strong></h3>

<p>Sometimes, the most useful information regarding preference can be gleaned from those who know the individual best. Asking caregivers informally, or by following a formal checklist, such as the <strong>RAISD, </strong>can be useful at identifying preferred stimuli.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h3><strong>Pre-Trial / Post-Trial Choice:</strong></h3>

<p>Sometimes, an individual&#39;s preferences change rapidly, or may change as a result of performing a task. For example, my preference for water <em>before exercise</em> might be low, but following exercise, might be very high. Because of this variability, some behavior analysts will ask before or after the demand so that the individual can select the item in that instant, based off their motivation in that moment.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h3><strong>Paired Stimulus Preference Assessments:</strong></h3>

<p>A&nbsp;<strong>paired choice</strong>&nbsp;preference assessment involves the presentation of 2 items at a time from a larger list (usually 7 - 12 items) to determine which items are the most preferred. Each item is presented in combination with every item on the list, so that the individual is given an opportunity to &quot;choose&quot; which item they like the most in a contest against every other item.</p>

<p>Often times, behavior analysts will ensure that the position (on the left, or on the right) of the various stimuli is evenly rotated to ensure that the individual is not just &quot;choosing the item on the right side&quot; (or exhibiting some other kind of position bias).</p>

<p>Food items are typically not intermixed with tangible items during preference assessments, as research suggests that some individuals may exhibit preference for food items over tangible items and skew results of such intermixed assessments.</p>

