INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (131,'<p>Which of the following is a type of preference assessment that uses a <strong>trial-based format</strong> to evaluate an individual&#39;s preferences?</p>','2018-09-29 16:59:57','<p>A&nbsp;<strong>preference assessment</strong>&nbsp;allows us to determine what stimuli are (and are not) preferred by an individual, by measure of how much time they spend interacting with an item (or the frequency of times they choose that item from an array of other items).</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>PLEASE NOTE:&nbsp;</strong>preference for a stimulus (like M&amp;Ms) does not necessarily imply that it will reinforce a <u>contingent</u> behavior! Reinforcer assessments are conducted when you need to demonstrate that a stimulus does have reinforcing value - preference assessments are typically done first to identify likely reinforcers.</p>

<p>Some big things to remember:</p>

<ol>
	<li>Things that you generally &quot;prefer&quot; to interact with in your free time (like, say, watching Netflix, Hulu, whatever) aren&#39;t the only reinforcers for behavior. For example, chapstick is a reinforcer (for the behavior of putting chapstick on my lips) but only when the EO (chapped lips) is present. Similarly, kleenex is a reinforcer (for the behavior of reaching for / buying / kleenex) but only when the EO (a runny nose) is present.</li>
	<li>A powerful reinforcer (coffee, ice cream, netflix - I&#39;m a simple man) may not be sufficient when the contingency is too demanding. For example, I will engage in high rates of &quot;button pushing&quot; to contact those items (uber eats; typing on a keyboard to find a show to watch; etc.). I will not engage in high rates of &quot;mowing the lawn of a football sized field&quot; to contact those reinforcers, however.</li>
</ol>

<p style="margin-left:40px"><strong>E.G.</strong> You offer me a plate with $1.00, a skittle, an M&amp;M, and a smiley face sticker on it.</p>

<p style="margin-left:40px">Each time I would probably choose the $1.00. You might write down &quot;$1.00 is the most preferred item&quot; and then attempt to use it as a reinforcer for a variety of tasks. If one of the tasks was touching my nose, sure, I&#39;d be likely to find that $1.00 very reinforcing for that behavior. However, if you change the response requirement to &quot;building a brick house&quot; I am unlikely engage in very high rates of &quot;house-building&quot; behavior when the contingency is $1.00. My motivating operations will be changed by the response requirement, in this case! So keep that in mind when utilizing the results of your preferrence assessments.</p>

<p style="margin-left:40px">Similarly, states of <u>satiation</u> and <u>deprivation</u> may alter the value of stimuli. Tokens, such as a $1.00, can be exchange for a great many reinforcers, which makes it hard to satiate on them. However, if I was only offerred food items during a reinforcer assessment, and you determined my #1, #2, and #3 favorite foods accurately, and then tried to use those items as reinforcers after I ate a big meal at lunch... you&#39;d probably get a lot less behavior out of me. Motivation matters!</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>There are many types of <strong>preference assssments</strong> - here are the different types:</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h2>Trial Based Preference Assessments</h2>

<p>Sometimes, behavior analysts will conduct formal preference assessments using the discrete-trial methodology: presenting a formal antecedent, expecting a response - in this case, a selection, and consequating that response with access to the selected stimulus. What follows are preference assessments in the &quot;trial-based&quot; format:</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h3><strong>Multiple Stimulus <u>WITH</u>&nbsp;Replacement</strong></h3>

<p>A&nbsp;<strong>multiple stimulus&nbsp;<u>with</u>&nbsp;replacement</strong>&nbsp;preference assessment involves the presentation of typically 5 - 7 items at a time to determine which items are the most preferred and allow you to identify what is the &quot;most valuable&quot; item(s) from the array. Typically, one item will stand out from it&#39;s peers in the array - such as a special toy, like a blankie, or the iPad, etc. - that the individual will choose each and every time they are given the option to. Knowing what this stimulus is on a day-to-day basis can make these types of preference assessments incredibly valuable, especially for learners who have difficulty communicating their choice.</p>

<p>It&#39;s best practice for behavior analysts to rotate the position of each item in the array&nbsp;to ensure that the individual is not just &quot;choosing the item on the right side&quot; (or exhibiting some other kind of position bias).</p>

<p>Food items are typically not intermixed with tangible items during preference assessments, as research suggests that some individuals may exhibit preference for food items over tangible items and skew results of such intermixed assessments.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h3><strong>Multiple Stimulus <u>WITHOUT</u> Replacement (MSWO):</strong></h3>

<p>A&nbsp;<strong>multiple stimulus without replacement (MSWO - yes, I know, the acronym MSWO is missing the &quot;r&quot; so that&#39;s confusing!)</strong>&nbsp;preference assessment involves the presentation of typically 5 - 7 items at a time to determine which items are the most preferred and create a hierarchy of those items. Since the items are not &quot;replaced&quot;, when the item is selected, it&#39;s gone for the remainder of that assessment, so typically the highest value items are selected first. This assessment is often repeated several times to determine the average &quot;rank&quot; of each item in the array.</p>

<p>It&#39;s best practice for behavior analysts to rotate the position of each item in the array&nbsp;to ensure that the individual is not just &quot;choosing the item on the right side&quot; (or exhibiting some other kind of position bias).</p>

<p>Food items are typically not intermixed with tangible items during preference assessments, as research suggests that some individuals may exhibit preference for food items over tangible items and skew results of such intermixed assessments.</p>

<h2>&nbsp;</h2>

<h2>Asking the Individual:</h2>

<h3><strong>Caregiver Report:</strong></h3>

<p>Sometimes, the most useful information regarding preference can be gleaned from those who know the individual best. Asking caregivers informally, or by following a formal checklist, such as the <strong>RAISD, </strong>can be useful at identifying preferred stimuli.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h3><strong>Pre-Trial / Post-Trial Choice:</strong></h3>

<p>Sometimes, an individual&#39;s preferences change rapidly, or may change as a result of performing a task. For example, my preference for water <em>before exercise</em> might be low, but following exercise, might be very high. Because of this variability, some behavior analysts will ask before or after the demand so that the individual can select the item in that instant, based off their motivation in that moment.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h3><strong>Paired Stimulus Preference Assessments:</strong></h3>

<p>A&nbsp;<strong>paired choice</strong>&nbsp;preference assessment involves the presentation of 2 items at a time from a larger list (usually 7 - 12 items) to determine which items are the most preferred. Each item is presented in combination with every item on the list, so that the individual is given an opportunity to &quot;choose&quot; which item they like the most in a contest against every other item.</p>

<p>Often times, behavior analysts will ensure that the position (on the left, or on the right) of the various stimuli is evenly rotated to ensure that the individual is not just &quot;choosing the item on the right side&quot; (or exhibiting some other kind of position bias).</p>

<p>Food items are typically not intermixed with tangible items during preference assessments, as research suggests that some individuals may exhibit preference for food items over tangible items and skew results of such intermixed assessments.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h2><strong>Free Operant Preference Assessments:</strong></h2>

<p>A&nbsp;<strong>free operant</strong>&nbsp;preference assessment allows learners freedom to roam an area, such as a play room, and interact with any items in the room they find motivating. The&nbsp;<strong>duration of engagement&nbsp;</strong>is recorded for each item, allowing analysts to compare the amount of time the individual spent with each item, and therefore determine if one item was more &quot;valuable&quot; than another simply by comparing the quantity of time the individual allocated to interacting with one item(s) over other(s).</p>

<p>There are two basic &quot;types&quot; of free operant arrangements:</p>

<h3><strong>Contrived:</strong></h3>

<p style="margin-left:40px">Typically, during a contrived free-operant assessment, these rooms are either &quot;seeded&quot; with likely high-preference items based off care-giver / parent / guardian report, which increases the likelihood of the assessment being successful at generating a hierarchy (or ranking) of preferred items.</p>

<h3><strong>Naturalistic:</strong></h3>

<p style="margin-left:40px">In this arrangement, the individual is observed where they typically spend most of their free or &quot;leisure&quot; time to identify how they allocate their responding.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><u>Citation</u><u>s</u>:</p>

<ul>
	<li>Cooper, John O., Heron, Timothy E.Heward, William L.. (2007) <em>Applied behavior analysis /</em>Upper Saddle River, N.J. : Pearson/Merrill-Prentice Hall</li>
	<li>DeLeon, I. G., &amp; Iwata, B. A. (1996). Evaluation of a multiple-stimulus presentation format for assessing reinforcer preferences. <em>Journal of Applied Behavior Analysis</em>, <em>29</em>(4), 519&ndash;533. http://doi.org/10.1901/jaba.1996.29-519</li>
</ul>',3,1,8,11);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (132,'<p>What is a <strong>developmental </strong>assessment?</p>','2018-09-29 17:20:56','<p>What follows are descriptions for various types of assessments - some assessments might meet all, some, or none of the criteria below. It is important to be familiar with these terms&nbsp;before using an assessment, so that you understand the implications of the assessment you are working with.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Developmental assessments</strong> assess skills based both on the individual&rsquo;s chronological age (how old they actually are) versus how old they are in terms of the skills they have learned in contrast to the skills typically learned by that age. This is referred to as their &ldquo;developmental age.&rdquo; The goal for clinicians using a developmental assessment is to calculate the difference between the client&rsquo;s chronological age and their developmental age, attempting to &ldquo;close the gap&rdquo; as quickly and efficiently as possible.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Criterion-based</strong>&nbsp;assessments involve presenting skills with specific criteria (an objective performance measure) that need to be mastered before the skill is considered mastered. These skills are typically organized into long-term goals, short-term goals, and instructional goals (from broader to narrow focus) for the convenience of the professional using the assessment.&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Curriculum-based </strong>assessments are assessments organized in a progressive manner, with suggestions and guides for progressing from one skill to the next as part of a coordinated curriculum. They give you examples of what to teach and in what order, and may also include teaching materials (such as worksheets, manipulative, sight word decks, etc.).</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Social skills </strong>assessments directly target social behaviors and often require the presence of one or more (or even groups) of similarly skilled peers. This is one of the inherent limitations of a social skills program - if the client does not have access to an environment with similar peers from whom social behaviors can contact reinforcement, no social skills program will be effective. Social skills curricula typical emphasize skills such as verbal behavior, understanding body language, defining and interpreting emotions of yourself and others, and other similar behaviors that typically produce socially mediated reinforcers. This can also include some &ldquo;a-social&rdquo; skills, such as brushing your teeth or wearing deodorant, as these skills impact your relationships with others (being &ldquo;stinky&rdquo; might repel others).&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Norm-referenced </strong>assessments calculate a quotient score, which can be compared against a standard of deviation to determine where the user performs compared to other persons using the assessment. For example, a score of 100 is &ldquo;average&rdquo; and reflective of typical performance on that assessment by typical members of the population the assessment is designed for (i.e., school kids in the first grade, or children at the age of 5). A score of 120 would be above average, and a score of 80 would be below average.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>',3,1,9,11);
