INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (140,'<p>What type of design is employed by a <strong>functional analysis </strong>to verify the maintaining variables of a given behavior?</p>','2018-09-29 19:26:03','<p>A&nbsp;<strong>functional analysis</strong>&nbsp;is a type of functional assessment where consequences for problem behavior are manipulated in an <u>experimental</u>*, <strong>alternating design</strong>&nbsp;to demonstrate which consequences are likely functional reinforcers for a given behavior.</p>

<p style="margin-left:40px"><em>** Note - in the context of behavior analysis, &quot;experimental&quot; does not necessarily mean &quot;untested&quot; or &quot;unproven.&quot; The word experimental indicates that the analyst is <u>verifying</u> a functional relationship. </em></p>

<p>It can be odd to conduct a functional analysis as the goal is unusual - from the onset, you are attempting to reinforce problem behavior. By testing multiple types of potential reinforcers, you identify what type of antecedents and consequences likely evoke and reinforce that problem behavior. Much like an allergy test involves exposing a patient to allergens to determine what you&#39;re allergic to, a functional analysis involves exposing problem behavior to the contingencies that maintain it to identify the &quot;source&quot; of the problem (i.e., the &quot;allergen&quot;).</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><u>Citation</u><u>(s)</u>:</p>

<p>Iwata, B. A., Dorsey, M. F., Slifer, K. J., Bauman, K. E., &amp; Richman, G. S. (1994). Toward a functional analysis of self-injury. <em>Journal of Applied Behavior Analysis</em>, <em>27</em>(2), 197&ndash;209. http://doi.org/10.1901/jaba.1994.27-197</p>

<p>Cooper, John O., Heron, Timothy E.Heward, William L.. (2007) <em>Applied behavior analysis /</em>Upper Saddle River, N.J. : Pearson/Merrill-Prentice Hall,</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>',3,1,10,11);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (141,'<p>What type of design is employed by a <strong>functional analysis </strong>to verify the maintaining variables of a given behavior?</p>','2018-09-29 19:29:21','<p>A&nbsp;<strong>functional analysis</strong>&nbsp;is a type of functional assessment where consequences for problem behavior are manipulated in an <u>experimental</u>*, <strong>alternating design</strong>&nbsp;to demonstrate which consequences are likely functional reinforcers for a given behavior.</p>

<p style="margin-left:40px"><em>** Note - in the context of behavior analysis, &quot;experimental&quot; does not necessarily mean &quot;untested&quot; or &quot;unproven.&quot; The word experimental indicates that the analyst is <u>verifying</u> a functional relationship. </em></p>

<p>It can be odd to conduct a functional analysis as the goal is unusual - from the onset, you are attempting to reinforce problem behavior. By testing multiple types of potential reinforcers, you identify what type of antecedents and consequences likely evoke and reinforce that problem behavior. Much like an allergy test involves exposing a patient to allergens to determine what you&#39;re allergic to, a functional analysis involves exposing problem behavior to the contingencies that maintain it to identify the &quot;source&quot; of the problem (i.e., the &quot;allergen&quot;).</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><u>Citation</u><u>(s)</u>:</p>

<p>Iwata, B. A., Dorsey, M. F., Slifer, K. J., Bauman, K. E., &amp; Richman, G. S. (1994). Toward a functional analysis of self-injury. <em>Journal of Applied Behavior Analysis</em>, <em>27</em>(2), 197&ndash;209. http://doi.org/10.1901/jaba.1994.27-197</p>

<p>Cooper, John O., Heron, Timothy E.Heward, William L.. (2007) <em>Applied behavior analysis /</em>Upper Saddle River, N.J. : Pearson/Merrill-Prentice Hall,</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>',3,1,10,5);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (142,'<p>While writing a mass email to all the patients at the behavior analysis clinic she works at, Sam cc (carbon copies)&nbsp; all of the families receiving services. What, if any, is the issue with this?</p>','2018-09-29 20:08:54','<p>The&nbsp;<strong>Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act</strong>&nbsp;has specific requirements for individuals who interact with&nbsp;<strong>Protect Health Information</strong>&nbsp;(PHI). Sharing protected health information is <u><strong>strictly</strong></u> prohibited; violating this policy can incur hefty fines as well as cost you your job. In addition, sharing protected information can irreperably damage an individual&#39;s trust with you and behavior analysis as a field - or even other mental health / service providers. This can cause an individual to forgo potentially life-altering treatment because of a silly, avoidable mistake. It&#39;s your responsibility to protect the privacy and dignity of every individual you serve.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Sam should use the <strong>bcc</strong> option (blind carbon copy) because the carbon copy option allows other recipients of the email to identify other patients at her clinic.</p>',7,1,37,9);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (143,'<p>Tammy is a BCBA working at a behavior analysis clinic. She is creating a flyer for an exciting workshop event at her clinic, and wants to share it with all the families currently receiving behavior analysis services, so she mass emails (cc - <em>carbon copy</em>) the entire roster of active patients at her facilty.</p>

<p>What, if anything, is wrong with this situation?</p>','2018-09-29 20:11:59','<p>The&nbsp;<strong>Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act</strong>&nbsp;has specific requirements for individuals who interact with&nbsp;<strong>Protect Health Information</strong>&nbsp;(PHI). Sharing protected health information is <u><strong>strictly</strong></u> prohibited; violating this policy can incur hefty fines as well as cost you your job. In addition, sharing protected information can irreperably damage an individual&#39;s trust with you and behavior analysis as a field - or even other mental health / service providers. This can cause an individual to forgo potentially life-altering treatment because of a silly, avoidable mistake. It&#39;s your responsibility to protect the privacy and dignity of every individual you serve.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Tammy should use the <strong>bcc</strong> option (blind carbon copy) because the carbon copy option allows other recipients of the email to identify other patients at her clinic (revealing their name, diagnosis, etc. - which is all, of course, PHI!)</p>',1,1,37,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (144,'<p>A little boy is playing with his toys in his room. Holding one of his stuffed animal dolls, he looks at it and says &quot;Zebra!&quot;</p>

<p>Which elementary verbal operant does this scenario most likely describe?</p>','2018-09-29 20:59:38','<p>A tact is labeling a non-verbal stimulus (i.e., not written words). Tacts are maintained by generalized social reinforcement (i.e., interaction / attention from others as a response to your tacting behavior).</p>

<p>In this scenario, the boy is labeling something seen in his environment.</p>',1,1,1,1);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (145,'<p>A child sees a cookie and says &quot;cookie.&quot; Without any knowledge of the child&#39;s motivation, what type of verbal operant does this mostly closely describe?</p>

<p><em>Be careful - this is a trick question!</em></p>','2018-09-29 21:02:48','<p><strong>Tacts vs. Mands:</strong></p>

<p>In real life, most verbal behavior is not &quot;pure&quot; - that is to say, it is under the control of multiple variables. When a child sees a cookie, they may say &quot;cookie&quot; as a tact (they are labeling the cookie) or as a mand (they want to eat the cookie) or, frankly, as both! Generally speaking, most of our verbal behavior is under multiple control like this.</p>

<p>For this question, as we are specifically not told the learner&#39;s MO, we are unsure if a mand is occurring. We must remember (and watch out for!) trick questions or tricky scenarios like this. Mands are only mands if there is a MO present. For the purposes of studying for an exam, most examples will be &quot;pure&quot; elementary operants like this.</p>',1,1,1,2);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (146,'<p>A child sees a pizza box and says &quot;pizza.&quot; Without any knowledge of the child&#39;s motivation, what type of verbal operant does this mostly closely describe?</p>

<p><em>Be careful - this is a trick question!</em></p>','2018-09-29 21:08:00','<p><strong>Tacts vs. Mands:</strong></p>

<p>In real life, most verbal behavior is not &quot;pure&quot; - that is to say, it is under the control of multiple variables. When a child sees a cookie, they may say &quot;cookie&quot; as a tact (they are labeling the cookie) or as a mand (they want to eat the cookie) or, frankly, as both! Generally speaking, most of our verbal behavior is under multiple control like this.</p>

<p>For this question, as we are specifically not told the learner&#39;s MO, we are unsure if a mand is occurring. We must remember (and watch out for!) trick questions or tricky scenarios like this. Mands are only mands if there is a MO present. For the purposes of studying for an exam, most examples will be &quot;pure&quot; elementary operants like this.</p>',1,1,1,2);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (147,'<p>It&#39;s right before lunch, and Sally is riding in the car with her mother. They pass her favorite fast food restuarant and Sally says &quot;Mom, can we get a burger? I&#39;m starving!&quot;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>What type of verbal operant does this most closely resemble?</p>','2018-09-29 21:13:16','<p>A <strong>mand</strong> is a verbal operant that is under the control of a MO (motivating operation). A &quot;pure&quot; mand occurs soley and spontaneously in the presence of the MO; however, a tact-mand can occur (i.e., you see / smell something yummy and then mand for the stimulus that corresponds to the tact).</p>

<p>Organisms with verbal behavior will only mand in a state of <u>deprivation</u> (i.e., they have not had access to the stimulus for some length of time). I will not mand for ice cream after eating so much that I feel like my stomach might burst (this is called <u>satiation</u>). However, I will mand for it on a hot day after having had nothing to eat for quite some time (<u>depriviation</u>).</p>

<p>A quick way to tell if a mand is a mand is to identify <u>motivation</u> - if there&#39;s no evidence of motivation, no mand is probably happening.</p>',1,1,1,2);
INSERT INTO `quiz_question` VALUES (148,'<p>Who wrote the book <em>Verbal Behavior</em> and famously founded <em>Radical Behaviorism</em>, a forerunner to what would eventually be <em>Applied Behavior Analysis</em>?</p>','2018-09-29 21:14:46','<p><strong>B.F. Skinner </strong>was the pioneer who founded <em>radical behaviorism,</em> which can be distinguished from the <em>methodological behaviorism</em> that preceded it by it&#39;s inclusion of thinking, feeling, and other private events in the analysis of animal behaviors.</p>

<p>Some of the concepts to emerge from Skinner&#39;s work include:</p>

<ul>
	<li>The cumulative record</li>
	<li>The S-R-S contingency or <em>Operant Conditioning</em></li>
	<li>The &quot;Skinner Box&quot; (or <em>Operant Chamber)</em></li>
</ul>

<p>&nbsp;</p>',1,2,1,2);
