<p>I have created practice quizzes for each <strong>content area</strong> - however, I&#39;d like to create &quot;A&quot;, &quot;B&quot;, and &quot;C&quot; versions for each content area so that folks can practice with new questions each time they try to train their skills.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>I&#39;d also like to program an &quot;account&quot; of some time, so folks can track their progress graphically. I have some experience working with <strong><a href="https://www.chartjs.org/">chart.js</a></strong>, but less experience working in Django / Python (which is what this site is built with). It&#39;ll be a learning experience but I expect it will be worth it! I would also like to build a dashboard so we as a community can see what questions are the most difficult / least valid, and use that feedback to improve the modules on this site.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Thank you all for your patience, feedback, and general awesomeness. I&#39;ll continue to work on this site in the coming months and I hope you all do excellently preparing for your exams!</p>','2018-07-08 17:18:43','2018-07-08 17:29:03',2,'p',349,72,'quizzes-tweaks-and-fixes-july',0,NULL,NULL,'Default');
INSERT INTO `blog_post` VALUES (10,'Motivation Matters','<p>I work typically with children with a diagnosis of Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD), and since some of my kids have really long days, I frequently find myself looking for items to motivate the clients I am working with. In the last 10 years, the quality and availability of &quot;reinforcers&quot; has experience a sea change, with the advent of the now ubiquitous iPad. Previously, behavior analysts (and before them, the <em>Behavior Modifiers</em>) were infamous for their over-utilization of edibles - snack foods, like candies, M&amp;Ms, etc. - as reinforcing stimuli.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>All this got me thinking - what are people using to motivate their clients in their sessions? Of course, I turned to the research, and I found this neat survey by Graff &amp; Karsten (2012) in <em>Behavior Analysis in Practice</em>.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><a href="https://i.imgur.com/0Ucnnjc.jpg" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/0Ucnnjc.jpg" style="height:443px; width:735px" /></a></p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>For those curious, <strong>the first iPad was released on April 3rd, 2010 </strong>and this study was in 2012. I wonder if they divided the &quot;toy&quot; category into &quot;screen time&quot; vs other types of toys, if there would be a difference of any kind between the BCBAs and the non-BCBA groups. One thing is clear, at least, from the data above - by 2012, behavior analysts are using a lot of varied reinforcement.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>For the behavior analyst working with young clients with autism, motivation is crucial. Many of young children will not respond unless motivational variables are contrived in some highly favorable fashion - natural reinforcers for behavior simply aren&#39;t enough for our clients (otherwise, they might not require the assistance of behavioral therapists!).</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h3>What are you using to motivate your clients, and do you match up with the results of the Gaff &amp; Karsten survey? Leave a comment below!</h3>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><u>Sources:</u></p>

<p style="margin-left:40px"><cite>Graff, R. B., &amp; Karsten, A. M. (2012). Assessing Preferences of Individuals With Developmental Disabilities: A Survey of Current Practices. <em>Behavior Analysis in Practice</em>, <em>5</em>(2), 37&ndash;48. <a href="http://doi.org/10.1007/BF03391822">http://doi.org/10.1007/BF03391822</a> </cite></p>

